INSERT INTO `country` VALUES (1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' AFN ','Afghan Afghani','Afghanistan','The government plans to implement a 10% VAT rate in 2022, which might result in net revenues of 1.2% of GDP, as well as phase out pandemic-related expenses, in order to reduce the growing budget deficit. Up to 60% of the money the Taliban make from opium trafficking and poppy farming (6.6 billion in 2021) comes from these activities. Finally, the nation is still receiving humanitarian relief from abroad. In early January 2022, the UN made an unprecedented emergency request for USD 5 billion. In December 2021, the World Bank announced the transfer of USD 280 million in humanitarian relief through the country\'s ARTF special fund. However, because debt rather than grants is being used to finance the deficit, the state debt, which has historically been primarily external and relatively low, is predicted to rise. The country received USD 10 million in debt service relief from the IMF in 2021, although financing this could be challenging. It is possible that a sovereign debt default will occur. The government will be able to access significant domestic savings through the first-ever Sukuk (sharia-compliant bond) issue, which is planned for early 2022. This will eventually spark the growth of a domestic debt market. Large inflows of grant money were used to partially bridge the current account deficit. The U.S.\'s suspension and freezing of the country\'s foreign exchange reserves, which are estimated to total over $9 billion (15 months\' worth of imports), has made it difficult for it to pay for its imports and compelled it to cut back on them. Since 10 December 2021, the United States has once again authorized expatriate remittances, which are a welcome source of cash. The United States, China, Russia and Pakistan, as part of the Troika Plus, are holding talks with Taliban leaders, aware that a deterioration would have repercussions on neighbouring countries and beyond (terrorism, drug trafficking, population exodus).'),(2,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' ALL ','Albanian Lek','Albania','Tirana intends to raise actual tax receipts in accordance with the pre-pandemic consolidation of state finances in order to decrease the deficit. In particular, the initiatives would focus on reducing exemptions and combating tax evasion. On the expenditure front, persistently high inflation would drive the need for additional assistance for low-income households and raise the price of investments. The government has relied on concessional financing for the 2022 budget due to civil unrest and an unfavorable debt structure. Albania\'s debt, which is mostly due soon, could be subject to foreign exchange risk because the local banking sector is still heavily based on the euro (50%). The Albanian current account deficit will continue to be among the biggest in Eastern Europe because of a limited export market. The key to the problems is the balance of goods, which will remain largely negative in 2023 due to a structural reliance on foreign trade for a variety of goods (machines, vehicles, pharmaceutical drugs, fuels, plastics, etc.), which is made worse by inflation and the need for investments. The balance of goods was negative at about 22% of GDP in 2022. The increase in tourism is anticipated to support the services surplus (9% in 2022), but the decline in remittances from expatriates as a result of the slowdown in the economies of Germany and Italy will not reduce the current account deficits, which should continue to be financed by FDI and concessional financing for infrastructure.'),(3,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' DZD ','Algerian Dinar','Algeria','Algeria\'s economic expansion in 2022 benefited from the sharp rise in hydrocarbon prices and the increase in demand in Europe as a result of Russia\'s invasion of Ukraine. The economic activity of the nation, which is heavily dependent on the energy industry, is anticipated to deteriorate in 2023 as a result of the falling income from oil exports. The latter will be related to the industry\'s constrained production capacity as well as the modest drop in oil prices, which will see a barrel of Brent fall from an average price of USD 100 in 2022 to an average price of USD 95 in 2023. Oil output is anticipated to plateau at about 1 million barrels per day in 2023 as a result of several years of underinvestment, decreasing the net contribution of exports. The economy should nevertheless grow steadily, supported by greater gas exports to Europe, which is looking for alternate energy sources to Russian gas. Production is anticipated to rise by 6.6% during the course of the year as a result of public and international investment in the gas sector. The non-hydrocarbon industry, particularly the construction and agricultural sectors, will also benefit from public and private investment. Last but not least, the government\'s social support programs for households, which account for 42% of GDP, are predicted to promote economic activity by growing by 2.7%. The latter, however, will continue to struggle in 2023 due to strong inflationary pressures. The base impact and slower global economic growth will cause a little decrease in inflation, but the central bank won\'t be able to, the central bank will be unable to bring inflation back to its flexible target of 3.5%.'),(4,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' ARS ','Argentine Peso','Argentina','Argentina’s frugality is anticipated to enter recession in 2023. Household consumption( 65% of GDP) is likely to shrink, dragged down by soaring affectation, a deteriorating job request and assuming an absence of new applicable income support measures. In fact, no enhancement is in sight to damp inflating consumer prices, amid elevated macroeconomic imbalances( including the large gap between the functionary and resemblant exchange rates) and strong import restrictions performing in dearths of consumer and goods and manufacturing inputs. Meanwhile, gross fixed investments( 17 %of GDP) should also contract, squeezed by tighter backing costs and investor caution towards the fragile profitable outlook and the forthcoming general choices. also, public investments should remain restrained due to financial tightening. Last, exports( 18% of GDP) are also anticipated to contract amid cooling global exertion( including in their main requests Brazil and the euro area) and dry rainfall conditions that will check the 2022- 2023 crop yields( wheat, soybean and conceivably sludge). Durably historically elevated husbandry commodity prices shouldn\'t neutralize the eventuality lower exported volume.'),(5,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' AOA ','Angolan Kwanza','Angola','Given that Angola\'s state finances are mostly dependent on the oil industry, favorable oil prices in 2022 helped Angola\'s fiscal situation and produced a respectable public surplus. However, the budget surplus will decrease in 2023 due to reduced oil earnings (which account for 60% of total income) and ineffective VAT collection. Despite persistently high levels of public spending, the price of oil will continue to be higher than the price required to achieve the country\'s budgetary balance (US$78 per barrel). By expanding social spending and keeping gasoline subsidies, the government will gain support. Additionally, Angola must pay back expensive debts, particularly to its Chinese creditor, who is responsible for nearly 40% of the nation\'s external debt (68% of GDP). Therefore, in 2023, debt service might account for 80% of state revenue. Despite the fact that it is still quite substantial, public debt is steadily declining as a result of recurring budget surpluses and kwanza trends. However, changes in the public debt stock will continue to be influenced by changes in the oil market.'),(6,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' AMD ','Armenian Dram','Armenia','The economy saw phenomenal growth in 2022 that had not been matched for 15 years. The tremendous migration of Russians and their capital into the nation, which has increased household consumer demand and the activity of some industries, most notably the information and communication technologies and construction, is largely responsible for this boom. While still strong, growth will be slower in 2023. Inflation will continue to restrain household consumption, which accounts for 69% of GDP and is the primary driver of GDP.Less remittances are projected to be sent home due to the Russian Federation\'s failing economy, which will have an impact on household spending (in 2022, more than 70% of all remittances made up more than 18% of GDP). The dram\'s increase in value in 2022 will aid in keeping inflation under control. The government\'s goal is to raise the percentage of investment in GDP to 25% by 2026 and that of direct investment overseas to 6% (2.6% in 2021). Gross fixed capital formation (17.5% of GDP in 2022) will once more positively impact growth.Net imports will still have a negative impact on growth, but how much will depend on how much trade Armenia has with Russia, which was its main trading partner in 2022. Given that inflation is higher than the CBA\'s target inflation rate of 4%, the key rate is now set at 10.75%, and the central bank has no plans to reduce it in the upcoming months. Foreign currency reserves, mostly in the form of foreign currencies, were equivalent to 5 months\' worth of imports in March 2023.'),(7,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' AUD ','Australian Dollar','Australia','Australian economic activity benefited from a robust post-pandemic recovery and favorable trade conditions in 2022 despite high global commodity prices. The unemployment rate is at a 50-year low, and labor market pressures reflect the strength of the economic recovery. In November 2022, the unemployment rate dropped to 3.4% of the labor force, leaving the economy with severe labor and skill shortages. Although wages have continued to climb slowly (3.1% year over year in Q3 2022), this has reduced the likelihood of a wage-price spiral. Australian economic growth is anticipated to decelerate, despite the tight job market (average unemployment rate at 4% of the labor force) in 2023. The sustained high level of inflation, which is creating a drop in real disposable household income, as well as a rapid rise in mortgage rates would hurt its main driver, private consumption (53% of GDP). Despite having one of the highest debt-to-disposable income ratios among industrialized countries (192%), Australian families may experience pressure from increased debt servicing expenses in some cases. According to the Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA), debt servicing might increase from 7% of household disposable income in 2021 to 9.25% by the end of 2023. Although rising mortgage rates will have an impact on consumption, due to cautious lending rules and high bank and household buffers, they are not anticipated to threaten financial stability. Private investment will be slowed down by inflation and monetary tightening, much as consumption. Because of government backing for renewable energy initiatives and the construction of transportation infrastructure, public investment should continue to be somewhat resilient. Finally, net exports will support GDP expansion.Net exports will be aided by China\'s reopening and a decrease in the cost of imports despite the slowdown in export growth brought on by the bleak economic outlook in Western trading partners and the downturn in China\'s real estate industry, which may have an impact on iron ore prices.'),(8,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' EUR ','Euro','Austria','In 2023, the economy is most likely to remain flat. The first half of the year saw a slowdown in activity, but the second half is predicted to see a gradual recovery. This uncertain outlook is caused by the divergent growth of the manufacturing sector, which has been in a recession since mid-2022 as a result of extremely low demand from its primary export market, Germany, and the brisk growth of services, particularly financial and economic services and tourism. The winter ski season of 2022–2023 was quite prosperous (only 5% less than the record season of 2019)In 2024, the manufacturing sector should gradually show signs of recovery in accordance with a mild recovery in Western Europe, including a nascent recovery in Germany, while service sector activity should continue to rise as a result of increased demand from tourism and the food and beverage industries. Together, these factors will help keep the economy growing in 2024.'),(9,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' AZN ','Azerbaijani Manat','Azerbaijan','The fiscal regulation was suspended in 2020 and then reinstituted in January 2022. It was modified in 2018 and now attempts to lower the non-oil primary deficit by limiting the rise of budgetary expenditure by 3% from one year to the next.The restoration also entails a target for debt repayment and an annual transfer from the State Oil Fund of Azerbaijan (SOFAZ) of USD 0.2 billion to the budget. Hydrocarbon windfall earnings have been spared along with reduced public spending. The numerous state-owned businesses continue to operate with significant inefficiencies, which will cause debt to reach around 30% of GDP in 2020.The peg of the manat to the dollar is supported by a strong balance of payments. Therefore, in July 2022, foreign exchange reserves were sufficient to cover imports for 7 months. The non-oil current account will stay constant at roughly a deficit of -20% of GDP, with the current account remaining particularly susceptible to hydrocarbon exports, which comprise on average more than 90% of goods exports.'),(10,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' BSD ','Bahamian Dollar','Bahamas','Despite the fact that energy imports accounted for 35% of GDP in 2022, the current account deficit shrank as a result of a pickup in tourism. In 2023, the tendency is anticipated to worsen. While the import bill and remittances from expatriates (3% of GDP in 2022) would decline, the surplus of the balance of services (tourist exports will expand by 4% of GDP in 2023) will continue to rise. The current account deficit will be closed via portfolio investments (5.9% of GDP by 2023) and FDI (3.4% of GDP by 2023). It should be highlighted that the imports of cruise ships by cruise passengers registered in the archipelago (10.7% of GDP in 2021) account for a significant portion of the current deficit. The FDI flow contains a complement to them. The peg of the Bahamian dollar (1 BSD = 1 USD) will be maintained by maintaining sufficient foreign exchange reserves (at least 5 months of imports).'),(11,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' BHD ','Bahraini Dinar','Bahrain','Bahrain\'s economy is predicted to grow less slowly in 2023 compared to the previous year, primarily due to lower oil costs, tighter monetary policy (caused by the dollar peg), and slower export growth (although net exports are projected to account for roughly 10% of GDP in 2023). Bahrain is one of the world\'s top manufacturers and exporters of aluminum, which makes up around 20% of all exports, but lower average steel and aluminum prices may restrain growth despite rising output. The contribution of net exports of goods and services to growth performance will also be hindered by Bahrain\'s important export markets, such as Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates (UAE), experiencing slower economic growth. Finally, a slowdown in tourism arrival growth in 2023 compared to 2022 would restrain the export of services (total tourist arrivals are projected to increase 20% YoY in 2023 vs. a leap of 171% YoY in 2022). Due to the slowdown in inflation, private spending, which accounts for around 40% of GDP, will continue to be the main growth driver.However, a tighter monetary policy will stop a significant increase because the demand for consumer loans will decline as interest rates rise. Second, the government\'s initiatives to improve Bahrain\'s business environment as part of the Vision 2030 program, which aims to lessen Bahrain\'s reliance on oil and gas, will continue to help the country attract significant foreign direct investments (FDI), which in 2022 increased by almost 6% to USD 34.5 billion from a year earlier. Large-scale investments have mostly been fueled by the USD 7.5 billion allocated by the GCC Development Fund as part of its USD 10.2 billion credit line for the years 2018 through 2024. However, as part of the Fiscal Balance Programme and the government\'s commitment to enacting spending-cutting measures in exchange for financial support from its Gulf neighbors, the contribution from government consumption will eventually decrease.'),(12,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' BDT ','Bangladeshi Taka','Bangladesh','The worldwide environment is dimming the prospects for the local economy, despite its fortitude in the face of the Covid-19 crisis and its subsequent good resurgence. Exports, which make up 12% of GDP in 2023, are projected to be impacted by weakening economic conditions in trading partners\' nations, particularly those in the European Union, which serves as its main export market. In particular, exports of textiles, which make up 80% of all exports, would decline in line with weaker international demand. Because of the nation\'s high energy consumption and persistently high energy prices, industrial production will be hampered by major electricity shortages and growing input costs. Additionally, the government\'s 50% increase in fuel prices in August 2022, high food prices, and anticipated increases in energy rates would all contribute to rising inflation and have a negative impact on domestic spending. Remittances, which will account for 6.2% of GDP in 2021, will nonetheless continue to support it due to the rising demand for labor in Middle Eastern nations.The government has budgeted considerable subsidies for gasoline, electricity, gas, and fertilizer as well as export and expatriate incentives for skilled employees to enhance diaspora finances for fiscal year 2023, which will result in a further increase in the fiscal deficit. Estimated at 1.9% of GDP, these subsidies and incentives may rise as commodity prices rise. Moreover, sales growth will continue to be modest.After hitting an all-time high in 2022, it is anticipated that the current account deficit will continue to be substantial but should gradually narrow, in large part because of the rise in remittances, relieving pressure on the balance of payments. Large external financing requirements in 2022 caused a squeeze on foreign exchange reserves, which should stabilize around about five months of imports. Additionally, the nation benefits from two IMF-awarded loans: a USD 1.3 billion Resilience and Sustainability Facility given in November 2022 and a USD 3.2 billion, 42-month Extended Credit Facility. These loans will relieve strain on the country\'s external position.\nNon-performing loans, the volume of which has escalated since the Covid-19 crisis, will continue to damage the financial sector, especially in the case of state-owned commercial banks.'),(13,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' BBD ','Barbadian Dollar','Barbados','Activity in 2022 was increased by the tourism sector\'s recovery (30% of GDP compared to 40% in 2019). In 2023, growth will fend off outside constraints. First off, despite the bleak Anglo-Saxon economic climate, tourism will continue to be the main driver of activity, accounting for 40% of jobs in 2022. In addition to the favorable effects of lower inflation on household income, economic growth will favor domestic spending (52% of GDP in 2022), notwithstanding a potential decline in remittances from expatriates, who are primarily from North America and are 2.5% of GDP in 2023. Additionally, private investment (15 percent of GDP in 2022) will rise in the financial, renewable energy, and tourism infrastructure sectors and will continue to offset the reduction in governmental investment (2 percent of GDP in 2022). Finally, there won\'t be much of an impact on industrial and agricultural production from the slowdown of CARICOM neighbors (73% of goods exports, excluding hardware, in 2021). While sales of medical reagents are predicted to rise sharply (by 7%), exports of petroleum (which will account for 21% of all exports in 2021), rum (17%), paper labels (4%), cement (3%) and margarine (3%) will expand only mildly.'),(14,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' BYN ','Belarusian Ruble','Belarus','In 2023, the recession will persist. The primary component of GDP, final consumption, which will account for 68% of GDP in 2021, and particularly that of households (almost half), will continue to suffer from chronic inflation.  Household purchasing power will decline as a result of real earnings growing slower than inflation. The government has however instituted inflation control starting October 2022, in part by establishing a price structure for producers, importers, and retailers. This mechanism states that price increases by industrial producers are only permitted when they are both economically justified and approved by a higher authority. Margin restrictions apply to importers and resellers. Less remittances from expatriates living there (more than 20% of transfers) will result from Russia\'s worsening economic state, although this will have essentially no effect on GDP (expat remittances made up less than 2% of GDP in 2021). Gross fixed capital creation, which will continue to contribute negatively to GDP growth and account for 24% of GDP in 2021, was already doing so before the conflict in Ukraine broke out. Net exports will have a beneficial impact, not because exports are recovering but rather because there is less demand for imports. Along with decreased household demand, sanctions imposed by the European Union, the nation\'s second-largest trading partner (20% of goods trade in 2021) are also to blame for the dip. These restrictions apply to Belarusian imports and exports and target important industries, including the 8% share of total imports that come from machinery and equipment imports and the 10% and 13% share of total exports that come from petroleum products and potash, respectively. In order to lower it by 50 basis points in January, the National Bank of the Republic of Belarus (NBRB) kept its benchmark interest rate constant at 12% till 2022. By raising the amount of foreign currency reserves required of banks, it also hopes to reduce the dollarization of the economy. Given the danger involved with the ruble and banks\' reluctance to hold this money, this operation may be challenging.'),(15,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' EUR ','Euro','Belgium','Although specific, Belgium\'s economic projection for 2023 is still largely in line with that of the rest of Western Europe. The energy mix is one unique component. Oil was the primary energy source in 2021 (47.7%), followed by natural gas (22.4%). What is notable is that while renewable energy sources account for 8% of overall energy consumption, nuclear energy accounts for 16.8% of the mix. Taking a look at the natural gas situation, Belgium was just 6% dependent on the Russian Federation before to the Ukraine War. Instead, the Netherlands, a close neighbor, is providing 33% of Belgium\'s gas needs, followed by Qatar (20%) and Norway (30%). In that regard, the LNG terminal in Zeebrugge is significant since the Belgian economy depends on a reliable gas supply. Belgian industry is the most gas-intensive in all of Europe due to its emphasis on the chemical and pharmaceutical industries. The government agreed to defer the phase-out of two nuclear power plants by ten years to 2035 in order to relieve strain on the energy sector. As a result, the nuclear energy industry was shut down that same year. To ensure energy security, significant expenditures on renewable energy sources and the building of more compact nuclear reactors are also planned. These initiatives will improve the future energy supply, but they had no effect on the significant increase in energy prices in 2022 that caused the inflation rate to reach its highest level since 1975 in October at 12.3%. While the inflation rate stabilized at the end of 2022, automatic wage price indexation in specific industries and in public-sector wages, as well as the adjustment of pensions over the first few months of 2023, will partially fuel the Belgian inflation rate and maintain it for a longer period of time than the rest of Western Europe.'),(16,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' BZD ','Belize Dollar','Belize','Oil price increases caused the current account deficit to widen in 2022 (hydrocarbon imports made up 10.8% of GDP in 2022), and it is predicted to modestly reduce in 2023.  The trade deficit will decline (to 27.7% of GDP in 2023 from 29.3% in 2022) as a result of the lower energy expense. The surplus in the balance of services (22.7% vs. 21.6% in 2022) will increase as a result of the tourism revival. In 2021, 5.4% of GDP in expatriate remittances, 94% of which originated in the United States, would make up for the gains that foreign tour operators repatriated. The current account deficit will be paid for by multilateral loans (at least 4% of GDP) and FDI related to the tourism sector (5% of GDP by 2023). It should be highlighted that the latter deficit (at least 6% of GDP in 2021) can be mostly attributed to imports of hotel equipment. Additionally, the Belizean central bank has enough reserves to preserve the currency peg (2 BZD = 1 USD)—these reserves covered at least 3.5 months\' worth of imports by the end of 2022.\n\nHousehold subsidies, specifically a decrease in the pay bill for the public sector, in 2022 weakened the fiscal balance attained by current expenditure limits. Even if a modest increase in the public deficit may occur in 2023 as a result of weaker economic growth. The primary surplus (i.e., excluding interest, which accounts for 1.2% of GDP) and debt servicing costs (1.8% of GDP) are both constant. First, on the strength of booming tourism and improved tax collection, tax revenues (23 percent of GDP for 2023) will continue. Second, due to continuing wage slowdown, public spending (22% of GDP) will stabilize. The increase in the minimum wage (5 BZD per hour) and the extension of subsidies will be offset by a decrease in social transfers (4.7% of GDP in 2023). The amount of capital spending (5.6% of GDP) is not anticipated to change, and it will be used mostly to build housing and infrastructure for tourism.\n\nThe public deficit will be financed on favorable terms through external loans, particularly those from the US government (International Development Finance Corporation). An agreement with The Nature Conservancy (TNC, an American environmental organization) at the end of 2021 made it possible to refinance the superbond due in 2034 (USD 553 million, or 30% of GDP) by issuing \"Blue bonds\" (USD 364 million maturing in 2041 with a 10-year grace period), which were arranged by Credit Suisse and came with political risk insurance from the DFC (US International Development Finance Corporation, an American development bank). The demand that Belizean authorities spend USD 180 million on marine conservation by 2041 and increase the share of its protected shoreline to 30% partially offsets the debt paydown (USD 250 million) and debt servicing savings (USD 200 million). A discount on Venezuela\'s PetroCaribe loan in 2022 brought down the debt burden to 4.4% of GDP. The debt burden has significantly decreased as a result of these two procedures, a robust economic recovery, the rebasing of GDP, and the primary surplus.'),(17,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' XOF ','West African Cfa Franc','Benin','Benin has enjoyed significant growth over the course of the period and kept experiencing robust growth in 2020 despite the pandemic, helped by a twofold increase in cotton production between 2014 and 2020. The specialization in this product and re-exporting create uncertainty, as seen by the recent plateau in yields and Nigeria\'s decision to close its borders in 2019 (much like it did in 1984). Although the establishment of an industrial foundation in construction materials, textiles, and agribusiness is encouraged, agriculture still predominates (30% of GDP and 40% of employment in 2021). The industry is still dominated by a de facto monopoly of \"white gold,\" or the buying and spinning of cotton, and in the Glo Djigbé industrial zone, textile manufacturers began to open in the fall of 2022. 2024 will see the end of raw cashew nut exports in an effort to encourage domestic processing.\nWhile state investment is anticipated to slightly decrease (from 7% in 2020 to 5.5% in 2023), it is not anticipated to return to its initial pre-pandemic level (20% of GDP) private investment (20% of GDP) is anticipated to remain constant. From 20% of GDP in 2016 to 27% of GDP in 2020, total investment has increased significantly, while household consumption as a percentage of GDP has decreased. Public investments, particularly in the electrical system (due to U.S. cooperation) and freight transport, have supported growth based on a crossroads position since the epidemic and the Ukraine conflict. Since 2017, the port of Cotonou has been enhancing its competitiveness with the assistance of the port of Antwerp\'s knowledge. In August 2022, Eiffage was awarded a contract of EUR 160 million to expand and rebuild the port by 2027. By lowering costs and waiting times, the enhancement in Panamax volume capacity, logistics handling, and administrative efficiency is intended to keep up with regional competitiveness. In addition, the pipeline connecting Agadem (Niger) and Port Sémé will be put into service by the China National Petroleum Corporation in 2023. The African Development Bank is funding the construction of the \"cotton road\" in the north between Djougou and Banikoara with USD 237 million, with work set to begin in October 2021 and completion anticipated in 2024.'),(18,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' BOB ','Bolivian Boliviano','Bolivia','The economy is anticipated to grow more slowly in 2023. Growth should be driven by household consumption, with inflation remaining consistently low. Due to the boliviano\'s peg to the USD, subsidies, and price controls on food and fuel, consumer pricing pressures have been restrained. However, as the nation\'s foreign exchange reserves rapidly diminish, there is a danger that the monetary authorities would be forced to abandon the USD peg, which would result in a large devaluation of the BOB and, consequently, a severe increase in consumer prices. The country\'s primary trading partners, Brazil and Argentina, would be less active, and prices for agricultural and mineral hydrocarbon commodities, which account for 28%, 10%, and 52% of 2022\'s foreign sales, respectively, would be softening. Despite government efforts to increase natural gas exports under Decree No. 4794 of September 2022, which limits the use of gas to power onsite operations by industrial recipients, this situation ought to prevail. The directive intends to prevent a severe worsening of the energy international trade balance due to the recent decline in domestic hydrocarbon production. The limited fiscal space will also constrain the increase of public investment, and the tougher global borrowing standards would restrain private investment. Bolivia has the greatest lithium reserves in the world, yet it is still unexplored and underexplored. To help tap into the vast reserves of the nation, the government in January 2023 agreed to an agreement with a group that included the Chinese battery manufacturer Contemporary Amperex Technology Co.'),(19,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' BTN ','Bhutanese Ngultrum','Bhutan','Significant hydropower potential that will continue boosting the economy, thanks to two new, important projects. Stable democracy with a low level of perceived corruptionAdequate perception of the rule of law. Landlocked, remote and isolated country in the middle of the Himalayas Rising dependency on hydropower exports to India. Persistently large annual current account deficits. High and rising level of external debt (116% of GDP in 2018)'),(20,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' BRL ','Brazilian Real','Brazil','Brazil\'s GDP increased by 1.9% YOY in Q4 2022 and 1.9% QOQ in Q1 2023, from 1.9% YOY and -0.1% QOQ respectively. However, the breakdown of the numbers shows a weaker and unequal economic trend. The weak domestic demand was highlighted by the positive external sector contribution on the demand side, which was driven by a greater decline in imports (-7.1% QOQ) than in exports (-0.4% QOQ). When it comes to the latter, household consumption growth actually slowed to a moderate +0.2% QOQ (from 0.4% QOQ in Q4 2022) while gross fixed investments decreased for the second consecutive quarter (-3.4% QOQ vs -1.3% in Q4 2022). Agriculture (+ 21.6% QOQ) provided significant support for activities on the supply side, particularly due to a record soybean production (after unfavorable weather circumstances in 2022). Looking ahead, the GDP is anticipated to slow down in the upcoming quarters as financing conditions remain strict and the favorable contribution from agricultural steadily decreases. The latter resulted in a severe decline in payment experience, and during the first five months of 2023, the number of businesses filing for Chapter XI protection increased by 51% YOY (the largest since 2018). The easing cycle should be fairly gradual, even though the central bank should begin lowering the policy rate in Q3 2023 since it has been held at 13.75% per year since August 2022. A still robust job market, social policies (including the increase in the real minimum wage and the extension of the Bolsa Famlia welfare program), debt renegotiation initiatives, and as inflation eases should all help to some extent strengthen household consumption, which accounts for 61% of GDP. Meanwhile, due to the continued tightness of the global financial environment, gross fixed investments are anticipated to decline marginally. The 2022–2023 crop outlook is promising, and relative growth in China—the primary export market—along with the relaxation of Covid-19 lockdowns will help exports expand even as the global economy falters (commodities will still account for 60% of global sales in 2023).\n'),(21,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' BGN ','Bulgarian Lev','Bulgaria','The prognosis for Bulgaria\'s economy is clouded by a number of uncertainties. Energy and food costs rose significantly across Europe in 2022 as a result of the conflict in Ukraine and the sanctions that followed between the EU and Russia, which had an indirect impact on the prices of other items. Bulgaria\'s prices rose to their highest level since 1998 in the autumn of 2022. While prices should continue to climb in 2023, the pace of this growth is likely to diminish, which should result in a decline in the inflation rate. In 2022, intense pricing pressure reduced both the willingness of private firms and families to make investments, and it should do so again in 2023. However, the business shouldn\'t face significant challenges due to a scarcity of energy commodities in 2023. Although Russia stopped supplying gas to Bulgaria in the spring of 2022, this can be offset by other energy sources because natural gas only makes up 11% of Bulgaria\'s energy mix (compared to the EU average of 24%). But when combined, energy from coal, nuclear, and oil accounts for 74% of total energy consumption. In fact, Bulgaria produces more energy than is used domestically. 131% of what is produced is being used. The impending mild recession in Western Europe during the winter and first quarter of 2023 is a major risk for 2023. The export of industrial intermediate items dominates the Bulgarian economy (total exports of goods and services account for 70% of GDP). The majority of exports (66.3%, with Germany accounting for 15% of all exports in 2021) are made to the EU. The net trade in products should have an impact on the GDP dynamic in 2023, even though the import-side should be essentially stable in 2023 compared to 2022. The amount of borrowing rates is another brake element. The policy of the Bulgarian Central Bank (BNB), which pegs the lev to the euro at BGN 1.96 per Euro (+/-15%), is similar to that of the European Central Bank. The BNB was able to maintain its key interest rate at 0% (the level since 2016) until September 2022, but then had to raise it to 0.6%. The BNB must gradually follow the same path as the ECB, typically with a time lag of several months, as the ECB already proceeded with four rate hikes totaling 250 basis points in 2022 and is anticipated to increase the interest rate further towards 3.5-4.0% by the end of 2023. This will drastically raise borrowing costs and have a negative impact on investment and consumption. However, there are also certain advantages to tourism that will contribute to the growth projection through 2023.'),(22,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' KHR ','Cambodian Riel','Cambodia','Despite challenges that resulted in weaker global economic development, Cambodia\'s real GDP increased in 2022, surpassing that of 2019. In spite of the worldwide economic downturn, Cambodia\'s GDP should expand a little quicker in 2023. Domestic consumption will continue to profit from the government\'s \"treating COVID-19 as endemic\" policy and the reopening of international borders after the nation began to accept unvaccinated travelers in October 2022 with no on arrival test required. Services like food and hospitality will have particularly strong demand. Having said that, tourism (26% of 2019 GDP) won\'t return to pre-pandemic levels as long as China, the country that used to be the top supplier of inbound travelers, adheres to its stringent COVID-19 policy. The majority of remittances (5.6% of GDP in 2019) come from Thailand, where the economic recovery is expected to continue in 2023, and they should be able to support household spending (73% of GDP in 2021). Investment will be fueled by the ongoing improvement in the business environment, which will be aided by the new 2021 Law on Investment and the Anti-Corruption Institution\'s 5-year action plan, which will run until 2025. A 10-year infrastructure plan that the government will present in 2022 may provide some respite for the construction sector, which has been struggling since the epidemic and contributed 15% of the economy in 2019. Although the country is heavily dependent on exports of goods and services (65% of GDP in 2021), particularly apparel and footwear (45% of total goods exports), the economy would be hurt by a slowdown in export growth. Rising recession risks in the biggest export destinations, the U.S. and the EU, would have a significant negative impact on export performance. The dominant textile industry would also continue to deal with rising prices for electricity and raw materials, which would be a double whammy.\n'),(23,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' XAF ','Central African Cfa Franc','Cameroon','The agri-food, forestry, services, and gas industries ought to serve as the foundation for economic activity in 2024, just as they did in 2023. LNG exports, which more than doubled between 2021 and 2022, could keep increasing as a result of the expansion of the Hilli Episeyo terminal\'s production capacity, which will reach 5 million tonnes annually in 2026 from 1.6 million tonnes in 2023. The continued growth of the port of Kribi also supports the expansion of the mining industry. The downturn in the oil sector will be largely mitigated by these developments. In 2024, the GDP investment share (17.5% of GDP in 2022) will remain constant. The National Development Strategy\'s ten-year plan, 2020–2030, is still in effect. By promoting industrialization through transportation (railways, port of Kribi) and energy (the Nachtigal hydroelectric power station, which should be operational by 2024 and supply the country with a significant portion of its electricity needs), it will allow the country to diversify its sources of growth. Despite the BCEAC\'s monetary tightening policy, inflation will continue to be above the 3% target set by the latter, having been primarily fueled in 2023 by food prices and the reduction of fuel subsidies that caused pump prices to increase by 15%.\n'),(24,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' CAD ','Canadian Dollar','Canada','Growth continued robust in 2022, supported by the advantages of loosening health constraints and rising commodity prices, particularly energy. However, towards the year\'s close, the impacts of inflation and quickly rising interest rates started to be felt, and it is anticipated that they will further stifle activity in 2023. They will have an impact on private consumption\'s (55% of GDP) contribution. Given their extremely high debt loads, Canadian consumers will be particularly susceptible to increased borrowing costs. However, their spending is likely to remain stable due to the savings made during the pandemic (about 12% of GDP), a robust job market at the beginning of the year (5.0% unemployment rate in December 2022), anticipated moderation in inflation during the first half of the year, and population growth brought on by vigorous immigration. In 2022, it is anticipated that residential investment, which has already been harmed by rising interest rates, would continue to decline. In 2023, construction will probably be impacted. On the other hand, robust private investment should be maintained despite the unfavorable rate environment by high commodity prices, the energy transition, and infrastructure projects. Energy and agricultural commodities (such as wheat) will continue to underpin export growth, but shipments of manufactured products should suffer due to the gloomy US economic outlook. The contribution of government spending will be extremely minimal since provincial and federal governments will make sure that fiscal policy does not clash with a strict monetary policy. The Bank of Canada is anticipated to maintain its benchmark interest rate at 4.5% in 2023 after increasing it by 425 basis points between March 2022 and January 2023. Prices for imports, energy, and food are anticipated to decline, which should assist to restrain inflationary pressures.\n'),(25,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' XAF ','Central African Cfa Franc','Chad','After years of negative growth (with some exceptions) for a population with a very low standard of living, the revival of the oil sector should continue to sustain the welcome recovery in 2023. This upturn is subject to many downside risks: continued food inflation and political instability, a prolonged interruption of IMF assistance (notified in June 2022) and threats to agricultural production (38.5% of GDP in 2019).\n\nThese risks also largely guide the decisions of foreign investors focused on the extraction of black gold. After Exxon\'s withdrawal took effect at the end of 2021, British buyer Savannah Energy announced in May 2022 an agreement on solar power plants with a combined capacity of 500 MW for its own installations and to supply cities. In June 2022, Glencore succeeded in selling its rights to the mature oilfield specialist Perenco. Despite high crude oil prices, the high extraction costs and the above-mentioned risks prompt oil companies to limit themselves to operating wells. Apart from oil assets (70% of exports in 2019), the disputed gold in the rebel-held Tibesti region (20%) and the robust cotton-grain sector (5%), the landlocked country relies heavily on imported manufactured goods. Nevertheless, the food bill remains low (~15% of imports) in view of the requirements of an acute humanitarian crisis, with the state relying on international aid.'),(26,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' CLP ','Chilean Peso','Chile','GDP data for the first quarter of 2023 confirmed the year\'s lackluster economic growth. Activity decreased by 0.6% annually from -2.3% in the fourth quarter of 2022 and increased by 0.8% quarterly from +0.2%. Despite the slight expansion, a weak composition is revealed by the breakdown. Exports only had a little expansion (+ 0.5% QoQ), while imports only saw a slight decline (-4.6% QoQ), which was the main driver of growth. As household consumption (-2.5% QOQ) continues to normalize in comparison to the high levels achieved in mid-2022, domestic demand decreased for the sixth consecutive quarter (-1.5% QOQ). Investments decreased during the time frame (-0.9% QOQ). A deteriorating employment market, persistently and historically high inflation (albeit slowing to some extent), restrictive lending conditions, and the dry-up of excess cash related to pension savings withdrawal will all have an adverse effect on consumer consumption in the upcoming quarters. While the central bank is likely to begin lowering its policy rate in Q3 2023—which was 11.25% annually at the beginning of July 2023—the downward trend should be slow. Furthermore, investors who are a little hesitant due to the protracted constitutional reform are influenced by credit conditions that are tight and tend to affect gross fixed investment (24% of GDP). Additionally, the recently enacted mining royalty statute and the government\'s April 2023 decision to only allow public-private partnerships with state supervision for future lithium contracts could partially derail upcoming investments. Exports, on the other hand, are anticipated to make a somewhat positive contribution as the economy begins to recover from the Covid-19 lockdowns and experience relatively greater growth there (the country that receives the majority of overseas sales). Although the demand for metal commodities has lagged behind (copper and lithium international prices YOY were on average lower in H1 2023, signaling a downside risk for Chilean exports), the Chinese trend has been driven by the services sector. In 2022, mining accounted for 57% of all exports, with lithium accounting for 8% and red metal for 45%.'),(27,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' CNY ','Chinese Yuan','China','GDP data for Q1 2023 confirmed the year\'s dismal economic growth. Activity decreased by 0.6% annually (down from -2.3% in Q4 2022) while increasing by 0.8% quarterly (up from +0.2% in Q4 2022). The breakdown demonstrates a weak composition, despite the modest expansion. The external sector drove growth, which was mostly supported by a decline in imports (-4.6% QoQ), while exports only had a modest increase (+ 0.5% QoQ). The domestic demand, on the other hand, declined for the fifth consecutive quarter (-1.5% QOQ), as household consumption (-2.5% QOQ) continued to normalize in comparison to the high levels reached in mid-2022. The period saw a decrease in investments as well (-0.9% QOQ). In the upcoming quarters, household consumption will continue to be a drag on activity due to restrictive lending conditions, a deteriorating labor market, persistently and historically high inflation (albeit slowing to some extent), and the drying up of spare liquidity related to the withdrawal of pension savings. Although the central bank is projected to begin lowering its policy rate in Q3 2023 (it was 11.25% per year in early July 2023) the decline should be gradual. Additionally, due to investors\' general caution regarding the protracted constitutional reform, tight credit conditions also frequently harm gross fixed investment, which accounts for 24% of GDP. A recent mining royalty statute that was enacted and the government\'s April 2023 decision to only allow public-private partnerships with state supervision for future lithium contracts could possibly somewhat jeopardize future investments. On the other hand, exports are anticipated to make a modestly positive contribution, led by somewhat greater growth in China (the primary recipient of international sales) as the economy begins to function again following the Covid-19 lockdowns. Though the demand for metal commodities has lagged behind (copper and lithium international prices YOY were on average lower in H1 2023, signaling a downside risk for Chilean exports), the Chinese trend has still been driven by the services sector. In 2022, 57% of all exports came from mining, with lithium accounting for 8% and red metal for 45% of the total.'),(28,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' COP ','Colombian Peso','Colombia','The first quarter of 2023\'s GDP numbers confirmed the year\'s lackluster economic growth. The level of activity decreased by 0.6% annually (from -2.3% in Q4 2022) and increased by 0.8% quarterly (from +0.2% in Q4 2022). Despite the minor enlargement, a weak composition can be seen in the breakdown. Exports only had a modest gain (+ 0.5% QoQ), but imports experienced a significant decline (-4.6% QoQ) that was mostly responsible for the growth. While household spending continued to normalize (-2.5% QOQ) in comparison to the high levels achieved in mid-2022, domestic demand contracted for the fifth consecutive quarter (-1.5% QOQ). Also declining over the time (-0.9% QOQ) were investments. In the upcoming quarters, household consumption will continue to be a drag on activity due to restrictive credit conditions, a worse labor market, historically high and persistent inflation (albeit it is slowing somewhat), and the drying up of excess cash related to pension savings withdrawals. Despite the fact that the central bank is anticipated to begin lowering its policy rate in Q3 2023 (which was 11.25% per year at the beginning of July 2023), the movement should be gradual. Furthermore, because investors are a little hesitant about the drawn-out constitutional reform, tight credit conditions also frequently harm gross fixed investment, which accounts for 24% of GDP. In addition, the government\'s April 2023 decision to only allow public-private partnerships with state control in future lithium contracts and the recently enacted mining royalty bill may also serve to partially derail future investments. However, when the economy begins to recover from the Covid-19 lockdowns, exports are anticipated to make a modestly positive contribution. This is largely due to China, which is the main country where overseas sales are made. However, the demand for metal commodities has lagged behind (copper and lithium international prices YOY were on average lower in H1 2023, signaling a negative risk for Chilean exports), and the Chinese trend has been driven by the services sector. 57% of all international sales were attributed to mining in 2022, with lithium accounting for 8% and red metal for 45%.'),(29,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' CRC ','Costa Rican Colón','Costa Rica','Activity was hindered in 2022 by external factors like the US recession and rising commodity costs. The growth will continue to slow down in 2023. First, it is anticipated that import inflation (oil, cereals, and intermediate products) will reduce private consumption, which will account for 64% of GDP in 2020. The reduction in purchasing power, which has been exacerbated by the growth in unemployment, will not be reversed by the regulation of fuel costs (1 litre of diesel is regulated at USD 1.18 and 1 litre of petrol is capped at USD 1.33). The National Bank of Costa Rica should further restrict access to credit (main policy rate of 9% at the end of 2022) in order to meet its inflation target of roughly 3% from the perspective of private investment, which accounts for 19% of GDP in 2021. Second, there is a chance that the economic slowdown in the US and Europe may increase foreign pressure. The US accounts for 43% of exports and the Netherlands for 39% of GDP in 2021, hence exports will decline. Bananas, pineapples, coffee, palm oil, fruit juice and concentrate, sugar, sauces and preparations make up 17% of exports, although agri-food production is predicted to decline. But the resilience of the tourism industry (which accounted for 47% of exports in 2021), the free trade zone (54% of exports in 2021), and the IT and medical sectors will prevent any chance of an economic downturn. Budget restraint, on the other hand, will affect general consumption. The construction industry will receive the majority of public investment following the ongoing hurricane devastation.'),(30,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' EUR ','Euro','Cyprus','Activity was hindered in 2022 by external factors like the US recession and rising commodity costs. The growth will continue to slow down in 2023. First, it is anticipated that import inflation (oil, cereals, and intermediate products) will reduce private consumption, which will account for 64% of GDP in 2020. The reduction in purchasing power, which has been exacerbated by the growth in unemployment, will not be reversed by the regulation of fuel costs (1 litre of diesel is regulated at USD 1.18 and 1 litre of petrol is capped at USD 1.33). The National Bank of Costa Rica should further restrict access to credit (main policy rate of 9% at the end of 2022) in order to meet its inflation target of roughly 3% from the perspective of private investment, which accounts for 19% of GDP in 2021. Second, there is a chance that the economic slowdown in the US and Europe may increase foreign pressure. The US accounts for 43% of exports and the Netherlands for 39% of GDP in 2021, hence exports will decline. Bananas, pineapples, coffee, palm oil, fruit juice and concentrate, sugar, sauces and preparations make up 17% of exports, although agri-food production is predicted to decline. But the resilience of the tourism industry (which accounted for 47% of exports in 2021), the free trade zone (54% of exports in 2021), and the IT and medical sectors will prevent any chance of an economic downturn. Budget restraint, on the other hand, will affect general consumption. The construction industry will receive the majority of public investment following the ongoing hurricane devastation.'),(31,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' CZK ','Czech Koruna','Czech Republic','Despite strong growth in the first half of 2022 fueled by the post-Covid recovery, the Russian invasion of Ukraine has subsequently had a significant influence on Czech economic activity. This impact will continue in 2023 when the Czech Republic\'s economy enters a state of stagnation. Due to a significant backlog of orders following supply chain disruptions in 2021, industrial output, which accounts for 38% of GDP, remained comparatively strong in 2022. However, industrial production is predicted to deteriorate in 2023. The industrial base of the nation, which is primarily supported by the automotive industry (which accounts for 10% of GDP and 25% of exports) and external demand, will be harmed by the lack of semi-conductors, high energy prices, and the deteriorating economic outlook of the Czech Republic\'s main trading partners, particularly Germany, which accounts for a third of the nation\'s exports. Therefore, notwithstanding the drop in imports, there would be a negative impact on GDP growth from international commerce. Private investment growth will also be negatively impacted by the current economic uncertainty, but public investment growth will be positively impacted by the EU\'s Recovery and Resilience Facility (RRF), which will provide grants totaling EUR 7 billion (3.1% of GDP) from now until 2026. Last but not least, private consumption will have a negative impact on the economic expansion, which has already been hampered by high food and energy prices and negative real wage growth, despite the strength of the labor market (unemployment rate at 2.4% in early 2023) and government anti-inflationary measures to support households. The inflation rate increased to its highest level since the 1990s after peaking at 18% in September 2022, causing the Czech National Bank (CNB) to raise its policy rate by a total of 675 basis points, or 7%, between June 2021 and June 2022. Although annual inflation will continue to be over the CNB\'s target level of 2%, it may decline as a result of both declining domestic demand and loosening energy markets.'),(32,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' DKK ','Danish Krone','Denmark','Despite robust export- and private investment-driven growth in 2022, the Danish economy is expected to moderately slow down in 2023 as a result of persistently high energy prices, inflation, and a decline in private savings. Since less than 1% of Denmark\'s exports and just 2% of its imports were from Russia, the Russian invasion of Ukraine had a little immediate effect on the Danish economy. As natural gas made up only 6% of the energy mix in 2021 (and can be replaced by other sources), compared to 48% for wind, 21% for bioenergy, and 16% for coal, it had a negligible direct impact. While the indirect effects of rising energy prices in Europe are spreading to the cost of food and other items due to higher production and transportation costs, the direct effects are limited. This caused the annual inflation rate in Denmark to increase to an average of 7.7% in 2022, which was the highest level since 1982, when the country was affected by the second oil price shock. Throughout 2023, consumer prices are anticipated to rise again, albeit more slowly than in 2022. The purchasing power of individual families is being reduced by price pressures. Additionally, with declining savings, consumption growth should continue to slow down over the winter and spring. The labor market is expected to continue strong in 2023, with job openings almost doubling their pre-pandemic level and an unemployment rate that hit a 14-year low. Denmark\'s central bank raised its benchmark interest rate by 320 basis points to 2.60% in 2022 and the first quarter of 2023 to stabilize inflation expectations and because the Danish Krone is pegged to the euro, and it is anticipated that it would follow the ECB for the rest of the year. Increasing interest rates would further restrain private spending, particularly home investment, as mortgage rates (mainly variable) already increased significantly in the second semester of 2022.'),(33,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' USD ','United States Dollar','Ecuador','In 2023, the economy is expected to fully fill the GDP gap triggered by the COVID-19 pandemic. Private consumption (roughly 62% of GDP) will remain the main driver of the economy amid a stable job market, and as consumer price pressures ease somewhat. Despite relevant fuel subsidies (estimated at 2.6% of GDP in 2022) and the fact that the economy is fully dollarised, domestic prices were not completely spared in 2022 by the sharp rise seen in international commodities. Meanwhile, gross fixed investment (21% of GDP) will increase at a slower pace, dampened by climbing global borrowing cost, by President Lasso’s lack of legislative support (hampering the passage of a more pro-business agenda) and by recurrent social pressures to stall projects due to environmental matters. Government spending (15%) will be moderated by the lack of fiscal headroom. In this regard, in September 2020, the previous Moreno administration and the IMF agreed to a 27-month Extended Fund Facility (EFF) for USD 6.5 billion, which Lasso’s administration took over after renegotiating and compromising over the pledge to cut public spending. Exports will grow, despite weakened global growth affecting the major markets for Ecuador´s foreign sales (such as the US, China, Panama and the European Union). Aquaculture -horticulture, agriculture, and agro-industry exports (chiefly shrimp, canned fish, bananas, cocoa and cut flowers) as well as crude- and refined-oil product exports (both of which contribute to 32% of total foreign sales) will slightly increase as their international prices remain at durably historically elevated levels, and Ecuador, which is no longer an OPEC member, is free to increase its oil production.'),(34,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' EGP ','Egyptian Pound','Egypt','According to the budget for 2022–2023, growth will significantly decelerate. The increase in unemployment and high inflation, which reached 33.9% on an annual basis in March 2023 (62.7% for food and 39.5% for the underlying), will have a negative impact on private spending, which accounts for 88% of GDP. The central bank increased its main rate by a total of 10 percentage points to 18.75% between March 2022 and March 2023. The bank\'s inflation target is 7% (plus or minus 2%). The central bank is anticipated to keep raising rates in order to return inflation to its target by the end of 2024. 12% of GDP) may be less likely to invest as a result of higher loan costs, especially since the central bank is expected to stop its practice of providing directed and subsidized credit. The dissemination of its economic policy will so be enhanced. By reducing local demand, monetary tightening also seeks to align it with production and import capacities. Fiscal restraint should have an impact on public consumption (7% of GDP) and investment (8% of GDP). In contrast, despite the weak status of the tourism industry brought on by a decline in Russian and Ukrainian (and Western) tourists, trade\'s contribution to the economy may be less detrimental. The Suez Canal income will be increased by the rise in LNG deliveries brought on by the expansion of liquefaction capabilities and the decrease in gas use for domestic electricity production. Positive effects will also come from the improvement in the terms of trade and the compression of imports brought on by both a scarcity of foreign currency and a slowdown in domestic demand. Due to growing prices and a shortage of imported inputs, manufacturing production (whose added value accounts for 15% of GDP) will continue to increase slowly. This will cause inflation. Agriculture (which accounts for 11% of GDP and 23% of employment) will continue to be subject to high input costs and government-imposed price controls. Due to the high cost of materials and the downward revision of non-essential public investments, construction (7% of GDP) would suffer.'),(35,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' EUR ','Euro','Estonia','The year 2022 was a difficult one for the Estonian economy. Estonia had to alter its international economic connections when Russia attacked Ukraine and many EU sanctions against Russia and Russian countersanctions went into effect. With a 6.4% stake, Russia ranked as Estonia\'s fifth-largest export partner. Russia was first in terms of imports in 2021, accounting for 11.6% of all imports. Natural gas, which made up roughly 7% of Estonia\'s energy mix, was one of the key products imported from Russia. Starting in March 2022, Estonia will no longer import any gas from Russia and will switch to more expensive liquefied natural gas (LNG) from the Lithuanian terminal at Klaipeda. The quay in Paldiski, which was initially designed for a floating storage and regasification unit that Estonia shared with Finland, was completed by Estonia. Although Estonia currently has the infrastructure to develop its own LNG-terminal, the FSRU will be placed in Finland.'),(36,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' ETB ','Ethiopian Birr','Ethiopia','The year 2022 was a difficult one for the Estonian economy. Estonia had to alter its international economic connections when Russia attacked Ukraine and many EU sanctions against Russia and Russian countersanctions went into effect. With a 6.4% stake, Russia ranked as Estonia\'s fifth-largest export partner. Russia was first in terms of imports in 2021, accounting for 11.6% of all imports. Natural gas, which made up roughly 7% of Estonia\'s energy mix, was one of the key products imported from Russia. Starting in March 2022, Estonia will no longer import any gas from Russia and will switch to more expensive liquefied natural gas (LNG) from the Lithuanian terminal at Klaipeda. The quay in Paldiski, which was initially designed for a floating storage and regasification unit that Estonia shared with Finland, was completed by Estonia. Although Estonia currently has the infrastructure to develop its own LNG-terminal, the FSRU will be placed in Finland.'),(37,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' EUR ','Euro','Finland','The Estonian economy experienced some turbulence in 2022. Estonia had to alter its international commercial relationships after Russia attacked Ukraine, leading to multiple EU sanctions against Russia and Russian counter-sanctions. With a proportion of 6.4%, Russia was Estonia\'s fifth-largest export partner. With 11.6% of all imports in 2021, Russia ranked first in the import category. Natural gas, which accounted for around 7% of Estonia\'s energy mix, was one of the primary imports from Russia. With effect from March 2022, Estonia stopped importing any gas from Russia and switched to more expensive liquefied natural gas (LNG) from the Lithuanian terminal at Klaipeda. The quay in Paldiski, which Estonia shared with Finland as part of a floating storage and regasification unit (FSRU), was completed by Estonia. Finland will install the FSRU, while Estonia currently has the facilities to construct its own LNG-terminal.'),(38,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' EUR ','Euro','France','At the end of 2022 and the start of 2023, the economy saw a significant slowdown as a result of weak domestic demand and ongoing inflation. The lifting of the fuel rebate and the 15% increase in electricity and gas tariffs on 1 January 2023 fueled inflationary pressures during the first half of the year, even though limiting the rise in gas and electricity prices (energy price cap) allowed the country to post the lowest inflation rate in the European Union over 2022 as a whole. Inflation should gradually decline in the second half of 2023 as a result of the establishment of price increases (underlying inflation of 5% in July 2023) and wage acceleration (+4.6% in the second quarter of 2023). Overall salary growth should outpace declining inflation in 2024, allowing households to experience an improvement in purchasing power. The environment will continue to be risky, encouraging precautionary saving, but household spending should increase. However, in a negative climate where the ECB will maintain very high interest rates until (at most) the second half of 2024, household property investment, which has been declining gradually since mid-2022, will continue at half-mast. Businesses that must contend with persistently low demand while also continuing to incur rising costs (rising wages, repayment of government-guaranteed PGE loans) will be significantly impacted by restrictive financing conditions (in terms of interest rates and lending criteria). Despite a noticeable decrease in investment and employment, business profitability and cash flow will be challenged in current circumstances. After two years of record low numbers, business insolvencies started to increase in 2022 and reached their pre-pandemic level in the first half of 2023 (up 2% from 2019). '),(39,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' GEL ','Georgian Lari','Georgia','After a surge in most economic sectors in 2022 and the effects of Russian immigration, growth will slacken in 2023. Final consumption will continue to be the largest source of demand, accounting for 94% of GDP in 2022 (at constant 2015 prices). The strengthening of the lari and the recent slowdown in inflation will have a beneficial impact on household demand, causing it to pick up speed. Gross fixed capital investment, which accounts for 17% of GDP, will continue to support GDP growth. In 2022, foreign direct investment represented 8% of GDP, with annual growth of around 60%. Nearly half of the FDI that came from the Netherlands in the first quarter of 2023 went to the manufacturing industry. Net exports of goods will once more have a negative impact on GDP growth. In terms of supply, Russian immigration and capital should continue to benefit services (11% of GDP), with tourism also serving as a mainstay.\nThe National Bank of Georgia (NBG) decreased its key rate by 50 basis points to 10.50% in May 2023, the first time it had done so since March 2022. The lack of second-round impacts (price-wages) and diminishing inflationary pressures, particularly from imports, were the driving forces behind the decision. The NBG did point out that geopolitical risk should be taken into consideration. At the monetary policy committee meeting in June 2023, the NBG policy rate remained at 10.50%.'),(40,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' EUR ','Euro','Germany','After a surge in most economic sectors in 2022 and the effects of Russian immigration, growth will slacken in 2023. Final consumption will continue to be the largest source of demand, accounting for 94% of GDP in 2022 (at constant 2015 prices). The strengthening of the lari and the recent slowdown in inflation will have a beneficial impact on household demand, causing it to pick up speed. Gross fixed capital investment, which accounts for 17% of GDP, will continue to support GDP growth. In 2022, foreign direct investment represented 8% of GDP, with annual growth of around 60%. Nearly half of the FDI that came from the Netherlands in the first quarter of 2023 went to the manufacturing industry. Net exports of goods will once more have a negative impact on GDP growth. In terms of supply, Russian immigration and capital should continue to benefit services (11% of GDP), with tourism also serving as a mainstay.\nThe National Bank of Georgia (NBG) decreased its key rate by 50 basis points to 10.50% in May 2023, the first time it had done so since March 2022. The lack of second-round impacts (price-wages) and diminishing inflationary pressures, particularly from imports, were the driving forces behind the decision. The NBG did point out that geopolitical risk should be taken into consideration. At the monetary policy committee meeting in June 2023, the NBG policy rate remained at 10.50%.'),(41,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' GHS ','Ghanaian Cedi','Ghana','Demand will be constrained by the strict economic policy anticipated in 2023 given the impasse in public finances. Due to the population\'s severe suffering from the 2022 price explosion and the subsequent collapse of purchasing power, consumption fell. Energy prices have increased by more than 50% despite the country\'s relative energy independence (crude oil, hydroelectricity), since the government has chosen neither to restrict prices or raise subsidies unduly. Given the uncertainties surrounding the currency rate and the austerity plan linked with the IMF loan, demand is anticipated to remain heated in 2023. Even while family savings are down, high inflation is projected to aggravate poverty (defined as below the USD 1.9/day criterion), which had decreased to 11.1% of the population in 2019 and further restrain consumption.\n\nGiven that household consumption accounts for over 70% of GDP and is the main driver of the economy, growth will be impacted proportionally. The banking industry\'s challenges, the tight monetary policy, and capital outflows are anticipated to have an impact on private investment in particular. After making a start in agri-food, fertilizers, vehicle assembly, aluminum, and steel, the creation of an industrial foundation (the One-District-One-Factory plan) will thus not advance greatly. A future savings strategy is also probably going to have a negative impact on public investment and lower it. The combined lowering of imported and exported food and fuel product prices in 2023 could maintain net exports\' contribution to GDP positive. However, the contribution of foreign commerce to growth will be diminished by illegal gold mining and smuggling, delays in the commissioning of offshore oil resources, and roasters\' market dominance on cocoa pricing. Since 2019, the Cocobod (Ghana) and the Conseil du Café-Cacao (Côte d\'Ivoire) have persisted in making joint demands to foreign buyers for cost of living and country of origin premiums, but so far they have not succeeded in reaching a concrete agreement.'),(42,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' EUR ','Euro','Greece','Greece\'s remarkable post-pandemic recovery will be significantly hampered in 2023 by ongoing inflationary headwinds and the resulting decline in purchasing power (for both Greek and European consumers). Greece\'s dependence on imported oil (which accounts for 50% of its energy mix) and foreign manufactured goods is significant given its persistently undiversified domestic industry. Greece has very little direct exposure to Russian energy supply and even to natural gas in general (which only accounts for 21% of the primary energy mix). The nation is currently experiencing a dilemma related to rising living expenses. Despite recent progress, it is predicted that unemployment will continue at 11–12%, indicating that despite the general tightening of the global labor market, Greek workers\' situation is still comparatively perilous. Furthermore, despite increases in the minimum wage, inflation-adjusted nominal pay growth is anticipated to lag behind. Fiscal spending initiatives, such as VAT reductions on energy items, direct subsidies to needy people and businesses, and retail energy price ceilings, will somewhat counteract this erosion. In essence, 5.7% of GDP is thought to go toward subsidies to people and businesses. Also likely to see a slowdown or a modest contraction are exports of goods (refined gasoline, food items, and pharmaceuticals), which are heavily dependent on European partners (61% of destinations). The cornerstones of resilience will be investment and service exports in the face of these challenges. The public sector and business were astonishingly quick to meet the tourism demand that had been building up. As a result, in 2022 tourist volume reached pre-pandemic levels and will increase in 2023. Greece is anticipated to continue to provide a wide range of investment opportunities despite an uncertain global economic picture. With grants and loans totaling about 18% of 2019 GDP over the period of 2021–2027, Greece will be the relative largest beneficiary of the EU Recovery and Resilience Facility. This program will ensure sustained demand for industries like construction, telecommunications, and renewable energy while creating favorable externalities that increase potential output. A sustained investor confidence has also been supported by major advancements in structural reforms (fiscal, market flexibility, elimination of red tape and bureaucracy, as well as consolidation of company balance sheets). The role of the eastern Mediterranean as a commerce hub is expected to grow as supply chains regionalize. Greece is a global leader in trans-shipping. An major downside risk is represented by the non-negligible possibility of a worsening of the global energy outlook.'),(43,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' HNL ','Honduran Lempira','Honduras','Price increases for imported raw materials and intermediates significantly slowed down activity in 2022. In 2023, growth will be able to withstand the US recession to some extent. The sharp decline in remittances from expatriates (20% of GDP, more than 90% of which came from the United States in 2022) and the rise in unemployment (7.6% of the active population in 2022) on the domestic consumption side (81% of GDP in 2020) will both be lessened by the renewal of subsidies to households for electricity and fuel. Second, the production of coffee (26% of all exports), vegetable oil (6%) and gold will be driven by global demand, accounting for 18% of GDP in 2021. Actually, just four Maquinadora products—computer equipment (18%), farmed shrimp (12%), bananas and melons (8%), will see a drop in production due to less advantageous export conditions in the United States (49% of exports in 2021) and Central America (18%). Third, public spending should increase as a result of Hurricane Julia\'s recovery operations, which cost the country USD 409 million by the end of 2022, and the new administration\'s infrastructure projects for education and health. Lastly, given the continually high level of insecurity, only a slight increase in private investment is anticipated.'),(44,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' HKD ','Hong Kong Dollar','Hong Kong, S.A.R.','In FY22 (April 2022 to March 2023) Hong Kong\'s fiscal situation worsened, mostly as a result of increasing public spending associated with the pandemic. However, as financial assistance programs for homes and businesses, such as unemployment benefits, government loan guarantees for firms, and unconditional electronic cash transfers to people, are lifted, its budget deficit is predicted to decrease in 2023. Despite continuous expenditures to address the population\'s quality of life problems, especially in regards to housing, the government expects to cut its overall expenditure by 6% to HK$761 billion. While increased fiscal spending and the implementation of aid measures caused Hong Kong\'s fiscal reserve to significantly fall over a three-year period, the government would issue additional green bonds to help the economic recovery. Over this time, it decreased by about 12 percentage points, and by FY24, it might only represent 24% of GDP. Nevertheless, Hong Kong\'s governmental debt, excluding the instruments required to control the currency board for the US dollar peg through exchange funds, continues to be modest.\n\n \n\nThe current account surplus is anticipated to continue to shrink in 2023 as a result of the fall in the trade surplus, notwithstanding reduced import prices for commodities and an increase in service exports. The rise in imports as a result of rising domestic demand will exacerbate the goods trade deficit. Growth in the services surplus will only partially counterbalance this trend. The latter will profit from the tourism industry\'s recovery and the financial services sector\'s ongoing success, as Hong Kong continues to be a desirable destination for wealth and asset management with connections to mainland China. Furthermore, the primary income surplus will continue, more than compensating the minor secondary income deficit, even if earnings repatriated by domestic enterprises will remain high. Hong Kong is already a significant creditor to the globe, with sovereign net foreign assets of roughly 130% of GDP and an international investment position of about 590% of GDP. The current account surplus will allow Hong Kong to amass external financial assets.'),(45,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' HUF ','Hungarian Forint','Hungary','The effects of the recession\'s lackluster economic activity, which began in the second part of 2022 and extended into 2023, will continue into 2024. Low household consumption is a result of the protracted era of high inflation, which has reduced disposable income. The first quarter of 2023 saw Hungary\'s inflation rate reach 25%, the highest in the European Union. Despite steady deflation in the months previous, consumer prices were still 20% higher in June 2023 than they were a year earlier. The causes for price acceleration are the same as in other nations: rising energy import costs and other negative economic effects of the war in Ukraine. Similar to the previous example, relatively decreased commodity prices have had less of an impact on inflation, which has seen general price increases that have expanded to other economic sectors, as evidenced by high levels of core inflation that still exceeded 20% in June 2023. But there are particular to Hungary\'s inflation as well: while the energy price limitations were relaxed, the food price caps remained in place, and as a result, businesses were rewarded with price rises for products not covered by the caps. Additionally, Hungary\'s 2022 harvests were subpar, which reduced supplies and raised prices for agricultural products. Last but not least, a permissive monetary and fiscal policy that began in the pandemic year 2020 and continued to include higher public spending in the run-up to the 2022 elections added to inflation pressure amid a robust labor market through double-digit wage growth. Additionally, the value of imported items increased as a result of the weaker forint.'),(46,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' ISK ','Icelandic Krona','Iceland','Due to the return of foreign tourists, which was still below the pre-pandemic level (-12% in Jan.–Nov. 2022 compared to the same period in 2019), the Icelandic economy was predicted to grow rapidly in 2022. Along with tourism, Iceland\'s economy has profited from high exports of fisheries and aluminum goods, which are sold very cheaply in comparison to other export commodities because of the significantly cheaper local energy/production costs (since Iceland is not dependent on the European gas market). Even though inflation reached 9.3% in November 2022, one of the highest levels since 2009, when Iceland experienced a severe recession following the financial crisis, consumer confidence remained persistently positive throughout the summer and fall of 2022. However, it is not anticipated that this powerful dynamic will last through 2023. This year, the downturn in Western Europe during the first quarter of 2023 poses the greatest risk to the Icelandic economy. The decline in purchasing power on both sides of the Atlantic (the US, UK, Germany, and France are ranked as the main countries of origin) will make it more difficult for individuals to afford longer vacations, which will cause a little slowdown in tourist arrivals in Q4 2022 and Q1 2023. Additionally, a fall in global demand, notably from the dominant European trading partners, would result in poorer growth for goods exports. Since most consumer and equipment goods are produced abroad, inflation pressures, which are primarily imported, will continue to be a major issue in 2023. As prices continue to rise but not as quickly as they did in 2022, the inflationary dynamic will likely slow down. As a result of the continuing decline in purchasing power, consumption growth should slow down during the 2022 winter season. However, a particularly large salary boost brought on by collective agreements at the beginning of 2023 would help restore some purchasing power. Unions will be in a strong negotiating position in 2023 as a result of the labor market\'s consistently high growth. This will raise inflation expectations once again, but the central bank is taking action by raising its benchmark interest rates six times in 2022, from 2% to 6%. Despite having already achieved their greatest level since the 2009 financial market crisis, the central bank is anticipated to carry out additional increases in 2023. Due to the high cost of financing, higher interest rates will continue to have a negative impact on investment and construction activities (possible danger for the housing market). Additionally, government assistance will continue to be small because there are few state-level policies in place to combat rising inflation, which is largely an imported problem unrelated to energy costs.'),(47,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' INR ','Indian Rupee','India','After Covid-19, India\'s economy had significant growth in 2022, with the momentum of that expansion shifting from goods to services. Private consumption (60% of GDP), which contributed over 80% to GDP growth in the first three quarters of 2022 compared to 60% the year before, was where this trend was most noticeable. The speed of growth in the commerce, lodging, and transportation industries rose to about 14% y/y in the same time, according to GDP data, which was also clearly visible in the retail services sector, a contact-intensive area. Even though it increased in 2022, fixed investment (29% of GDP) had a significantly less contribution to growth than in 2021. Due to the negative shock to trade brought on by the rise in input and commodity prices, net exports were a bigger drag on GDP.\nThe prognosis for India\'s economy in 2023 would be hampered by a global downturn and further normalization of domestic fiscal and monetary policies. However, we anticipate that the Indian economy will continue to grow quickly, helped by domestic demand. The rebound in urban employment is likely to aid in the continued recovery of consumer spending, and there may be an increase in rural income due to greater rabi harvests. The purchasing power of households will also increase as inflationary pressures decrease.\nIn 2023, the country\'s capital spending will be more heavily influenced by the central government\'s sustained emphasis on infrastructure investment through flagship programs like the National Infrastructure Pipeline and the National Logistics Policy. In the period from April to September 2022, central government capital spending (capex) increased by 50% year over year to 3.42 trillion rupees, and a subsequent rise was announced in the FY2023–24 budget in February 2023. Private sector investments would be stimulated by the government\'s supply-side efforts to promote manufacturing, such as the Make in India initiative, a production-linked incentive program, a program for semiconductor and display manufacturing, and continuous supplier diversification. After years of deleveraging and an increase in profits during the pandemic, which drove corporate debt (52% of GDP in Q3 2022) to its lowest level since 2005, private enterprises are likewise in a stronger financial position to increase capex.\nIn contrast, the forecast for exports of goods and services is dim in 2023 because advanced economies\' development is predicted to significantly slow down. As a result, the negative impact of net exports on GDP will probably expand and slow India\'s rate of economic expansion.'),(48,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' IDR ','Indonesian Rupiah','Indonesia','Despite a deteriorating global economy, Indonesia is expected to experience strong development in 2023. The recovery in private spending (56% of GDP), which has come with the gradual lifting of Covid-related measures and the restoration of overseas travel in 2022, will continue to be beneficial to the economy. Therefore, it is anticipated that services associated to tourism, such as catering, hospitality, and transportation, will grow especially quickly. The job market will improve, which will aid in the recovery. In the third quarter of 2022, Indonesia\'s unemployment rate was 5.9%, down from the 7.1% recorded in the same period of 2020.  Consumers should continue to profit from manageable inflation, even though it should continue to be high in 2023 as a result of the increase in gasoline prices introduced in September 2022 and the recovery of the economy. Having stated that, in August 2022, Bank Indonesia began to tighten its monetary policy in response to the weakening of the Indonesian rupiah versus the US dollar and growing headline and core inflation. The central bank had increased its policy rate by a total of 225 basis points as of the end of January 2023. The demand from households is probably to suffer from tighter monetary conditions. Private investment ought to be impacted by this as well. In addition, a law passed in December 2022 permits the central bank to support public debt during economic downturns by purchasing government bonds on the primary market. Investors may become concerned because this reduces central bank independence.  Nevertheless, the continued economic recovery and the anticipated implementation of the Omnibus Act, which aims to deregulate labor reforms and foreign investment laws, will spur private investment. Infrastructure initiatives, particularly those related to transportation, digital technology, and the creation of a new capital city, will underpin public investment in the meanwhile. The stronger travel sector and rising commodity prices could help Indonesia\'s exports, which account for 23% of GDP and for which the country is a net exporter of goods including coal, gas, and palm oil. The latter, however, will expand more slowly due to a decline in worldwide demand. Additionally, new or more stringent export rules could affect performances for export. The government implemented such regulations for palm oil in 2022 and 2023 in an effort to rein in price increases. Palm oil exporters were required to ship six times their domestic sales volume as of January 1, 2023, down from eight previously. In the meantime, a bauxite embargo is anticipated to go into place in June 2023, this time to improve local processing.'),(49,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' IRR ','Iranian Rial','Iran','Iran\'s development would be hampered by the drop in oil prices and external competition on the energy market, particularly from Russia. As fiscal revenues from hydrocarbon sales (almost 15% of total revenues) are constantly constrained by ongoing US sanctions, a slowdown in government consumption will reduce GDP growth. In contrast, slower riyal depreciation (which between the end of 2022 and the end of May 2023 lost 20% of its value against the USD on the black market) and lower food costs globally will cause annual inflation to slow to 40% in 2024 from almost 50% in 2022. As a result, household consumption (which accounts for about 45% of GDP), will somewhat accelerate. Additionally, investment (which accounts for 35% of GDP) will steadily increase over the next few years, mostly as a result of the return of diplomatic relations with Saudi Arabia in 2023 and growing Russian investment. With a total investment of USD 2.76 billion, the latter became Iran\'s biggest foreign investor in 2022. The outcome of continuing discussions and diplomatic initiatives to resurrect the Iran nuclear deal will also have an impact on the nation\'s economic prospects in 2023 and 2024. Iran\'s economic prospects may be enhanced if indirect discussions with the US result in a relaxation of international sanctions through increased foreign investment and easier access to markets. According to the BMI, oil production is predicted to increase by 0.5% from a year earlier to 3.7 million barrels per day (9% of GDP) in 2024, based on demand from China and other Asian nations, where Iran competes with Russia. Whatever the development in that area, the need for structural changes, the underdeveloped private sector, the high degree of bureaucracy, and the poor business climate will continue to pose difficulties to Iran\'s growth.'),(50,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' IQD ','Iraqi Dinar','Iraq','Following a very severe economic downturn in 2020 brought on by the Covid-19 epidemic, followed by two years of remarkably strong economic development brought on by very high hydrocarbon prices, growth slowed in 2023 as a result of falling oil prices and the temporary suspension of Kurdistan\'s oil exports to Turkey. Therefore, growth in 2024 is likely to be modest due to factors such as OPEC\'s decision to maintain its production cuts, oil prices being moderated by a still weak global economy, and the February 2023 dinar revaluation that made exports less valuable in local currency. Iraq is OPEC\'s second-largest producer. Investment initiatives supported by the USD 150 billion budget authorized by Parliament in June 2023 for the years 2023–2025 will be the main drivers of non-oil GDP development. This would make it possible to implement infrastructure projects, like as the 2022-starting, 2024-predicted repair of Mosul Airport, which was partially destroyed in 2017 during the conflict with Daech. A major portion of the budget will also be allocated for existing government expenditures, such as boosting the minimum wage, which will support private consumption. The revaluation of the dinar, which will reduce imported inflation, and the return of inflation to a moderate level as a result of falling food costs worldwide would also encourage the latter.'),(51,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' EUR ','Euro','Ireland','The Irish economy is anticipated to decline in 2023 after two years of double-digit expansion as a result of a variety of causes, the main one being price increases that began in 2022 and are anticipated to continue, albeit to a reduced extent, in 2023. Despite the slowdown in the economy, Ireland will continue to be one of the few in Europe to see growth rates above 1% in 2023, in part because of the activities of multinational corporations with Irish headquarters that operate in less cyclical industries like IT and pharmaceuticals.\n\nInflation is predicted to have peaked in 2022, but because prices are sticky—core inflation was around 6.9% in May 2023—there being a tight labor market, increased pay expectations, and price stickiness, it will likely remain over the ECB\'s 2% objective.  From a historical perspective, energy prices will remain high in 2023, with oil and natural gas accounting for the majority of energy in Ireland (78% of the country\'s energy mix in 2021). \n\nDomestic consumption will slow in 2023 as a result of inflation since families\' disposable income will be lower due to a second year of declining real income. In Q1 2023, private consumption began to decline. In Q1 2023, after inflation adjustment, wages decreased by 3.0%. However, the savings rate for Irish households is still high (18% in Q1 2023 compared to 11% in Q1 2019). \n\nDespite ongoing investments from international corporations and a strong pipeline in the first half of 2023, capital investment will be hampered by high operational costs, rising input and labor prices, and high interest rates, which combined with global unpredictability will discourage investments by businesses.\n\nThe UK and EU, Ireland\'s two biggest trading partners, will go into a recession in 2023, or at the very least, there will be economic stagnation. The decline in household spending power will cause imports as well as exports to decline. The value of imports will continue to be exaggerated due to high energy prices.\n\nDespite an increase of 21% from Q1 2019 to Q1 2023, corporate insolvencies nevertheless remain low as compared to prior quarters. Corporate insolvencies are anticipated to increase further in 2023 as businesses continue to struggle with rising costs at the same time that many government support initiatives are being phased out.'),(52,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' EUR ','Euro','Italy','Following Draghi\'s retirement in July, a far-right alliance easily won the September 2022 quick elections with 43% of the vote, as was predicted. Giorgia Meloni, whose Fratelli d\'Italia (FdI) received 26% of the vote, is in charge of the new cabinet. She is joined by Matteo Salvini\'s Lega (9% of the vote) and Forza Italia (8% of the vote), both of Silvio Berlusconi. Despite his convincing electoral triumph, Meloni will still face formidable obstacles if he wants to hold onto his position for the long term. She may quickly lose favor with anti-establishment supporters due to the necessity to reach concessions with the European Commission and reassure investors, to name one. Second, if Meloni loses enough support from the general public due to policy and interpersonal differences, Salvini is likely to defect. Although Meloni has expressed a strong desire to work with the EU, this will be put to the test as her popularity declines. To qualify for bond purchases under the ECB\'s Transmission Protection Instrument (anti-fragmentation tool), Italy must maintain positive relations with the EU. The biggest political danger in Italy continues to be the ongoing instability of the executive, despite the positive surprises brought on by the tone the Meloni cabinet set. There is a good likelihood that the Meloni administration will fall before the end of its term. Italian populist parties frequently gain support while in opposition before losing it swiftly once they are elected. If not, disagreements with other European governments may arise on issues like immigration and the drafting of new EU fiscal regulations.'),(53,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' JMD ','Jamaican Dollar','Jamaica','Despite a strong post-pandemic recovery in 2021 and a revival in the tourism industry (which accounts for 35% of GDP) and mining exports (which account for 10% of global bauxite output), activity slowed down dramatically in 2022 due to inflation. Given that household consumption accounted for 76% of GDP in 2021, the decline is likely to be confirmed in 2023. Their discretionary income will be reduced by inflation, particularly as a result of high commodity prices. Additionally, as US and global economy stagnates, the reduction in expatriate remittance flows (about 20% of GDP in 2019) is anticipated to undermine incomes. Increasing unemployment, which could reach above 8% (6.6% in mid-2022), would likewise have a negative impact on consumption.   However, activity will continue to be fueled by export revenues, which in 2019 will account for almost 30% of GDP. Tourism (58% of exports in 2019) could continue to improve despite pressure on the purchasing power of American, Canadian, and British consumers, who made up almost 90% of tourists in 2019. It will be accompanied by mining exports, which will progressively rise as the Alpart bauxite and alumina factory resumes operation (20% of exports in 2019). The major markets for this production will be China and the United States. Business activity will also profit from investment support, particularly through public-private partnerships initially slated for 2021 and 2022 in infrastructures for logistics, mining, and tourism, such as JISCO\'s investments in the Essex Valley and the building of the Caymanas-to-Ocho Rios highway. They would aid the building industry. But the contribution of public consumption to economic activity will be constrained by fiscal restraint.'),(54,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' JPY ','Japanese Yen','Japan','Japan\'s economic growth slowed in 2022 compared to 2021 as a result of the effects of Covid-19, high commodity prices, and supply-side restraints. In the second half of 2022, there was a stronger recovery in gross investment (25%) and private spending (55% of GDP). But because of high import costs, a decline in travel spending because of border restrictions, and a slowdown in international trade, net exports started to become a bigger drag on GDP. As import value increased 74% year over year in 2022, Japan\'s trade deficit (JPY 19.97 trillion) was the highest in more than 40 years since 1979.\n\nIn 2023, Japan\'s domestic demand will probably remain strong despite the global decline. As consumer voluntary caution wanes, reopening momentum will continue to enhance household consumption. Consumer spending will also benefit from the likelihood of real wage growth turning positive on anticipated high nominal rises during spring wage negotiations (shunt), as well as from a reduction in surplus household savings, which are projected to account for 10% of GDP. The outcome of wage negotiations will also play a significant role in determining changes to monetary policy. The Japanese economy will also be supported by strong momentum in capex. Corporate enterprises have started to considerably increase capex since mid-2022, with the September 2022 quarter showing a 9.8% y/y increase. Data revealed significant capex increase in both manufacturing and non-manufacturing sectors, including construction, wholesale and retail trade, information and communication electrical equipment, and services. Corporate capex in 2023 will be supported by a strong domestic need for continued investment in sustainability, digital transformation, and solutions to address the labor shortage.\n\nThe recovery of industrial production will be aided by the reduction of supply bottlenecks, while the auto industry may continue to experience supply frictions, as noted by major automakers, which may restrict output. Japan\'s GDP growth will be significantly hindered by declining global demand. Japan\'s exports increased by 18% y/y in 2022, which is similar to the 22% increase in 2021, thanks to the ongoing normalization of supply chains.'),(55,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' JOD ','Jordanian Dinar','Jordan','Despite a high unemployment rate (approximately 23% in Q1 2023), private consumption—which accounts for 75% of GDP—is anticipated to continue to be the main driver of growth. Subsidies for food and energy will also keep the inflation rate in check. The main rate of the central bank was 7.5% as of July 2023 compared to 2.5% in February 2022, but consistently high commodity prices and tight monetary policy will continue to drive up construction costs. However, given the government\'s desire to increase the nation\'s renewable energy resources, notably solar power, investments (about 20% of GDP) are anticipated to sustain growth performance. Jordan wants to raise the percentage of renewable energy sources in its energy mix from 20% to 50% by 2030. Growth will also be supported by public investments in transportation infrastructure. The government unveiled two construction projects in July 2023 that cost a total of USD 780 million and involved building a sports city and a tourism hub. Foreign capital as well as funding for regional development should support these initiatives. A new USD 400 million healthcare project in Amman will require construction management services, and in Q4 2022, the Saudi Jordanian Fund for Medical Educational Investment Company (SJFMEI), a fully owned subsidiary of the Saudi Jordanian Investment Fund (SJIF), signed an agreement with Dar Al Handasah Consultants to provide those services. According to the IMF program, it is anticipated that government spending (which accounts for around 20% of GDP) will continue to be subpar, notwithstanding the continuation of social subsidies for lower-income people. After the Jordan-EU free trade agreement went into effect in 2022, net exports, which currently account for around 15% of GDP and are mostly comprised of phosphate, potash, and apparel, will be crucial to growth. In 2024, tourism-related revenues are predicted to reach USD 16 billion, or 30% of the global GDP, a projected rise of 20% over the previous year. Jordan will still be dependent on imports, which will lessen the GDP contribution of net exports.'),(56,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' KZT ','Kazakhstani Tenge','Kazakhstan','In 2023, growth will continue. Inflation will continue to have a negative impact on final consumption, the biggest component of GDP (63% of GDP in 2021), and particularly households\' final spending (43%). Real wages might not rise in line with inflation, which would reduce the purchasing power of the average household. Remittances from expatriates living there will decrease due to the worsening economic climate in Russia (44% of transfers), although this will have essentially no effect on GDP (remittances from expatriates represented less than 0.5% of GDP in 2021). GDP will increase as a result of gross fixed capital creation, which will account for 27% of GDP in 2021. Since at least a few years ago, it has been growing as a percentage of GDP; in 2022, the manufacturing sector received almost half of all investments (an increase of around 6% annually). In 2023, this pattern will continue. The government\'s top priority are to diversify the economy and invest in structural projects, including the development of the manufacturing sector, regional infrastructure projects, SMEs and entrepreneurship, as well as transportation and the gas transport system. Although net exports will increase GDP, they will be partially offset by imports of capital goods and intermediate goods as well as lower-than-expected oil prices. Following multiple rises in 2022, the National Bank of Kazakhstan (NBK) has kept its benchmark interest rate at 16.75% since December 2022. Despite an inflation peak reached in December 2022, the NBK claims that the current rate is acceptable due to uncertainty and the lack of a downward trend. With a target range of 15.75–17.75%, this rate should contribute to stabilizing and thereafter steadily lowering inflation, which is the NBK\'s goal.'),(57,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' KES ','Kenyan Shilling','Kenya','Despite the uncertain environment surrounding the August 2022 general elections and the contraction of the agricultural sector (37.5% of GDP) due to the severe drought in the Horn of Africa, Kenya has continued its post-pandemic economic rebound which has been driven by robust activity in the services sector (46.5% of GDP). In 2023, economic growth will continue despite fiscal and monetary tightening, durably high inflation and a deteriorating global economic environment. Increased private investment, driven by credit growth and renewed investor confidence following the peaceful transfer of power in government, will contribute to economic momentum. Despite the use of Public-Private Partnerships, public investment will be deterred by tighter fiscal policy and higher borrowing costs due to the large stock of public debt and high inflation. Export growth is also expected to decelerate, affected by the slowdown in demand from the European and US economies on the one hand, and the persistence of drought on the other. Kenya could suffer, for the fifth consecutive year, from a missed rainy season when its agricultural activity provides the bulk of exports. However, the slowdown in export growth will be more than offset by the slowdown in import growth due to lower world energy prices, so that the contribution of net exports to growth will be positive. Similarly, consumption (81% of GDP) will support economic activity as household disposable income increases, driven by falling inflation. While inflation rose in 2022 on back of the sharp depreciation of the exchange rate (10% against the dollar) and rising oil prices, the Central Bank of Kenya raised its benchmark interest rate by 250 basis points from May 2022, bringing it to 9.5% in March 2023. While this decision should help ease inflationary pressures, food prices, which are highly dependent on rainfall, pose a significant upside risk to inflation forecasts in 2023.'),(58,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' KWD ','Kuwaiti Dinar','Kuwait','Due to reduced oil prices and an expected 4% reduction in OPEC+ oil production in 2023 (oil accounts for close to 50% of GDP), Kuwait\'s economic development was essentially nonexistent. In 2024, growth is predicted to resume thanks to an increase in crude oil and refined fuel exports, the latter made possible by the Al-Zour refinery\'s extra capacity for processing. From a projected 1.05 million barrels per day in 2023, the total refining capacity is predicted to increase to 1.4 million barrels per day in 2024. A steady increase in oil prices will ease pressure on public spending (hydrocarbons make up about 70% of fiscal receipts), while lower inflationary pressures are anticipated to benefit private consumption, which accounts for around 30% of GDP. Public investment would increase as a result, expanding Kuwait\'s oil fields. However, aside from some significant infrastructure projects (such as employment centers, the development of the Mubarakiya markets, a cultural and entertainment center on Abdullah Al-Ahmad Street in the Sharq region, etc.) in the works as part of the government\'s Vision 2035 project aimed at diversifying the economy away from oil, investments in the non-oil economy are likely to be minor. This is primarily due to a difficult operational environment (lack of transparency, insufficiency of regulatory On the other hand, the government\'s plan to create a new sovereign fund to aid in local economic diversification and support is a step in the right direction towards putting economic reforms into place. On the strength of gradually rising oil prices and output, net exports, which make up around 25% of GDP, will contribute more to growth in 2024. However, its contribution will be offset by the nation\'s reliance on imported goods and services. Despite sticky inflation in the services and housing sectors due to insufficient supplies, mostly because of a lack of private sector activity, inflation is predicted to slow down in the upcoming quarters. This is mainly because of the downward sliding goods prices. Due to the exchange rate peg regime and the high anticipated US dollar content of the secret currency basket, the central bank is predicted to adopt the same strategy as the US Federal Reserve in 2024.'),(59,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' KGS ','Kyrgyzstani Som','Kyrgyzstan','After a remarkable year in 2022, growth will decrease in 2023 and be fueled by increasing household consumption demand, which will result in part from the direct immigration of Russians to the region and in part from an increase in remittances from those who have left the country. Due to persistently high inflation and decreased transfers (27% of GDP in 2022), primarily from Russia (95% of transfers and 25% of GDP in 2022), final consumption, which represented 101.2% of GDP in 2021, will decline in 2023. Gross fixed capital investment, which accounts for 23% of GDP, will boost growth. Net foreign direct investment should continue to contribute little to the GDP in 2023 (0.5% in 2022 and 2.5% in 2021). The Kambar-Ata-2 hydroelectric power station, which is situated on the Naryn River and will produce electricity for Kyrgyzstan, Kazakhstan, and Uzbekistan, is one of the nation\'s main investment projects. This plant\'s development was decided in January 2023. Even if gold exports have recovered (but have since stopped in 2022) net exports will continue to have a negative impact on growth.'),(60,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' LAK ','Lao Kip','Laos','The recovery was hindered by increasing costs (CPI annual increase broke 30% in August 2022, a 20-year high) and supply interruptions tied to massive import bills and a lack of foreign cash (FX) the following year after being held back by Covid-related measures in 2021. Economic growth should continue to be hampered by these two conditions in 2023. Given the projected trajectory of inflation in 2022, second-round impacts are anticipated to persist until 2023 and are extremely likely to have an impact on household consumption, which accounted for 66% of GDP in 2016. A comeback in foreign visitor numbers would be delayed in addition to China\'s zero-COvid policy by the context of rising inflation and supply restrictions, particularly if fuel and food shortages materialize. 10% of GDP in 2019 was attributed to tourism, which fell to 2.9% in 2021. Meanwhile, strong demand for copper and power should propel exports despite a global slowdown in trade. Additionally, the China-Laos railway, which starts operations in late 2021, will benefit copper, which is primarily shipped to China. The completion of various projects in 2022, such as Nam Theun 1 Hydropower, will help with electricity exports, which are primarily destined for Thailand. The industry will expand as a result of increased investments, particularly in the Monsoon Wind project, the largest wind energy project in Southeast Asia, with a capacity of 600 megawatts anticipated by 2025. As a result, building would increase (34% of GDP in 2021). The agriculture industry, which accounts for 15% of the GDP and 61% of employment in 2019, would also be impacted by high prices since rises in the cost of gasoline, animal feed, and fertilizer would have an impact on production. Having said that, providing low-interest loans to regional food producers so they can purchase agricultural inputs could lessen this negative impact.\n\nIn order to increase Laotian kip demand and so reduce imported inflation, the Central Bank of Lao (BOL) issued bonds in Laotian kip in response to the inflationary rise. Despite this, BOL\'s extremely low reserves (1.7 months of imports in September 2022) prevented it from taking significant action to stabilize the weakening kip.'),(61,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' EUR ','Euro','Latvia','The conflict in Ukraine in 2022 stopped Latvia\'s economy from expanding. Russia was Latvia\'s fourth-largest import partner and fifth-largest export partner in terms of goods trade due to their proximity. Prior to the conflict, they made up 9.4% of all exports and 11.5% of all imports of products into Latvia, together with Belarus, a smaller trading partner. The equipment industry, which accounts for 16% of Latvia\'s exports and was previously heavily dependent on Russian steel and iron, is being particularly negatively impacted by the current EU sanctions and is now forced to rely on other more expensive suppliers. The pharmaceutical industry, whose revenue fell by 30%, agriculture, and the wood industry are all affected by issues with the supply of input products from Russia that have been either stopped by the EU or by counter-sanctions. Imports of fertilizer and lumber have also decreased by half over the summer of 2022. High energy prices and supply unpredictability have a significant influence on the entire economy, despite Latvia\'s efforts to lessen its reliance on Russian imports (which, as of mid-2022, accounted for 31% of Latvian energy consumption). Russian gas imports will be prohibited starting in January 2023. Due to the high level of input costs as well as the decline in export markets, all businesses are suffering. A significant downturn in Western Europe likely result in fewer exports to the EU, but some of this will be offset by increased shipments of wood due to EU bans on Belarusian wood imports. While the inflation rate should decline in 2023 on the back of lower price pressure than in 2022, progression of the purchasing power will remain low, even if wages are partially adapted to the higher price level at the beginning of 2023. Household consumption will suffer as a result of the strong increase in prices, which, with an increase of around 2% in autumn 2022, reached its highest level since Latvia\'s independence. '),(62,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' LBP ','Lebanese Pound','Lebanon','Despite an improvement in growth performance in 2024 due to favorable base effects, a pickup in inbound tourism (estimated at 15% of GDP in 2024), and an increase in remittances from expatriates (38% of GDP as of 2022), the Lebanese economy will continue to be severely stressed. However, due to lack of confidence and persistently high inflation in line with sharp local currency depreciation, growth in private consumption, Lebanon\'s traditionally largest contributor to GDP (around 100% of GDP), will remain muted. At August 2023, its official rate had lost about 90% since the economy started to collapse in October 2019, while the parallel rate and central bank-administered Sayrafa rate used for customs were about six times higher than the official rate. The Lebanese pound may be officially devalued more as inflation expectations weaken. Public consumption, which makes up about 15% of GDP, and investment, which makes up 10% of GDP, would be affected by the limited budgetary flexibility. Private investment will be badly impacted by weak infrastructure (limited electricity supply from Electricité du Liban) and a bad business climate characterized by a high perception of corruption and onerous bureaucracy. Regional instability, ongoing operational, and logistical issues all hurt exports. Syria continues to have a restricted capacity for food and beverage production, which limits exports. On the other hand, the protracted economic crisis puts pressure on domestic demand, which depends significantly on imports, preventing a further expansion of the detrimental impact of foreign trade on GDP. Due to security concerns that can influence international tourists\' decisions to travel to the country, growth in tourism revenues is predicted to be about 10% in 2024 rather than the 25% rise predicted for 2023. Due to a lack of an efficient monetary strategy and growing (imported) food prices, inflation will continue to be extraordinarily high. Current political unpredictability and declining confidence will accelerate dollarization and hence drive inflation. Although the impact of the tripling of customs taxes, fees, and duties on all imported goods in March 2023—customs taxes will be calculated at 45,000 Lebanese pounds to the dollar, up from 15,000 pounds to the dollar previously—will gradually diminish, shortages of basic goods will not be affected by this. Without exchange rate unification in these conditions, monetary policy is unlikely to be able to control inflation.'),(63,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' LYD ','Libyan Dinar','Libya','Since 2011, Libya has gone through two civil conflicts, which have damaged the country and given rise to armed organizations with a tribal affiliation. Colonel Gaddafi was removed from power in 2011 following 42 years of dictatorial leadership. The second was started in 2014 by the self-declared and ragtag Libyan National Army (LNA) under Marshal Haftar. It was initially directed against the Islamists, but it was quickly joined by the House of Representatives, which was elected in 2014 and is based in Tobruk, and was directed against the internationally recognized government of El-Sarraj, which is based in Tripoli. Early in 2020, Turkey indirectly participated during a Haftar offensive on Tripoli that was supported by Russia and Egypt, restoring some of the power balance. In October 2020, a truce negotiated by the UN that supported the establishment of a Government of National Unity (GNU) brought this second conflict to an end. The GNU was designed to serve as a transitional administration until late 2021, when general elections might be held. Due to their postponements, there are currently two governments vying for power in the nation: the National Stability Government (NSG), headed by Fathi Bashaga and backed by the House of Representatives in Sirte (East), and the GNU, led by Abdelhamid Dbeibeh and the High State Council in Tripoli (West).'),(64,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' EUR ','Euro','Lithuania','The economy of Lithuania was expanding rapidly. However, the situation drastically shifted after Russia invaded Ukraine. In 2021, Russia was Lithuania\'s top commercial partner, accounting for 10.8% of its exports of goods and 12.1% of its imports. Sanctions and trade restrictions are now having an impact on these trade flows. The same holds true for Belarus, which was the eleventh export destination (3.0%) and Lithuania\'s ninth-largest trading partner in terms of products imported in 2021 (3.5% of all items imported). Oil and gas made up the majority of Russia\'s imports. In fact, in 2021, 83% of the Baltic nation\'s oil imports and 40% of its natural gas imports came from Russia. Nevertheless, in mid-May 2022, Lithuania became the first nation in the EU to halt all energy imports from Russia. This is mostly due to Lithuania\'s ability to diversify its gas sources thanks to the LNG terminal in Klaipeda, which is located on the country\'s coast, and the Klaipeda pipeline into the interior. But achieving energy independence from Russia had a hefty cost. The headline inflation rate in early fall 2022 was 24% year over year, the highest of all the Eurozone countries, due to skyrocketing energy and food prices. This was the highest inflation rate for Lithuania since 1996. Consumer prices are anticipated to rise even more in 2023, albeit more slowly than in 2022. As a result, the inflation rate should significantly decline while continuing to be very high. Consumer purchasing power has been severely reduced as a result of the consumer price explosion, with private consumption accounting for 62% of nominal GDP in 2022 and private investments for 22% of GDP. Both the decline in savings and the increase in interest rates will have a negative impact in 2023. Given the extremely favorable labor market position, private consumption may continue to be slightly more robust than investments in this context. By the end of 2022, the unemployment rate will have fallen to about 8.3%, which is below the pre-pandemic level. This might increase consumer assurance. The ECB\'s monetary policy will have a significant influence on interest rates. '),(65,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' EUR ','Euro','Luxembourg','Luxembourg\'s economy was resilient throughout the epidemic because of its focus on financial services, which account for 27% of its GDP and have always been robust. With EUR 5,800 billion in assets under management in Q2 2022, the nation is the second-largest investment fund hub in the world after the US. Seven of the 130 institutions surveyed in 2019 were commercial banks with a domestic market emphasis, making up the majority of the financial sector, which is made up of foreign banks (subsidiaries of European banks) and alternative investment funds. The sector will be impacted by the global monetary tightening, geopolitical tensions, and the high level of uncertainty in the world economy, particularly the prospects of a stagnation in the euro area, despite the diversity of its activities and its solid capitalization. While wage increases (indexation planned for April 2023 in particular) and support measures (reduction in VAT, cap on gas and electricity prices) will partially offset the downward trend in inflation that began at the end of 2022, households will still limit their consumption in an environment where cautionary savings are encouraged. Due to a lack of available homes and rising mortgage rates, household investment in real estate will also decrease. Additionally, the Grand Duchy appears to be equally vulnerable to an energy crisis as the rest of the region given that it imported 40% of its gas from Russia prior to the Ukraine War and that its gas market is integrated with Belgium\'s. Public investment, which will continue to be significant (at about 4% of GDP), will also support activity in order to boost economic competitiveness and hasten the ecological and digital transformation.'),(66,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' MYR ','Malaysian Ringgit','Malaysia','Due to its focus on financial services, which account for 27% of GDP and have historically been robust, Luxembourg\'s economy remained resilient throughout the epidemic. After the US, the nation is the second-largest investment fund hub in the world (assets under management: EUR 5,800 billion in Q2 2022). The financial sector is primarily made up of foreign banks (subsidiaries of European banks) and alternative investment funds; of the 130 institutions examined in 2019, seven were commercial banks with a domestic focus. Despite the variety of its activities and its robust capitalization, the industry will be impacted by the tightening of global monetary policy, geopolitical unrest, and the high level of uncertainty in the global economy, particularly the anticipation of stagnation in the euro region. Even though wage increases (indexation planned for April 2023 in particular) and support measures (reduction in VAT, cap on gas and electricity prices) will help offset some of the inflation, which should continue its downward trend that began at the end of 2022, households will still limit their consumption in an environment that encourages precautionary savings. Due to a lack of housing, high prices in the sector will increase household investment in real estate, which will also fall when interest rates rise. Additionally, because the Grand Duchy\'s gas market is integrated with Belgium\'s and it imported 40% of its gas from Russia before the Ukraine War, it appears to be just as vulnerable to an energy crisis as the rest of the region. Public investment will also support activity, which will continue to be significant (about 4% of GDP), with the goal of boosting economic competitiveness and advancing the ecological and digital transition.'),(67,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' MVR ','Maldivian Rufiyaa','Maldives','After the instability between 2020 and 2022, which led to one of the world\'s worst recessions and was followed by an equally spectacular recovery that was fueled by a rebound in international travel and supportive government measures, growth has steadied since 2023. The tourism industry, which in a typical year directly contributes 25% of GDP or 60% when adding allied industries like food providers, is extremely important to the economy. In a broad sense, the service sector is responsible for 78% of GDP. Due to the Maldives\' popularity as a travel destination for Chinese citizens before the pandemic and its approval by the Chinese government at the end of 2022, growth will continue to be largely driven by the tourism industry, which will benefit from the uptick in Chinese tourism. This will counterbalance the weaker purchasing power and decreased robustness of tourism from the European Union and the United States, as well as the rising competition from some increasingly alluring locations, such as Thailand. This will be combined with arrivals from India and Russia. Tourism-related industries like transportation and retail will benefit from this. Major public investments, notably in infrastructure to assist tourist, will also benefit business. The Velana International Airport extension project will continue, but the largest project in the territory, the Greater Malé Connectivity Project, which aims to build a road connection from the capital Malé to the islands of Villingli, Gulhifalhu, and Thilafushi, is scheduled to be finished by the end of 2024. Due to lower import prices for food and energy as well as a potential gradual reduction in public spending in favor of households once the presidential election in September 2023 and the parliamentary election in March 2024 are over, inflation is predicted to moderate in 2024 after two years of high inflation, which is typically very low. Private consumption will be slightly impacted by this budgetary crunch.'),(68,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' MOP ','Macanese Pataca','Macao S.A.R','The recovery in Macao SAR is anticipated to continue in 2022, but it will be a while before the economy reaches its pre-crisis level. Although Macao SAR\'s casino businesses\' strong financial position and robust fiscal support cushioned employment and consumption, the rapid reduction in activity highlighted Macao SAR\'s susceptibility to outside factors that affect visitor inflow. A resurgence of the COVID-19 epidemic and an increase in the stress in Macao SAR\'s banking sector are two short-term dangers to the forecast. The pandemic\'s severe effects on Macao SAR\'s development emphasize the necessity of diversifying the local economy away from the casino sector. Long-term issues are raised by the significant susceptibility to climate-related shocks.'),(69,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' EUR ','Euro','Malta','Malta\'s economy is faring better than other European economies in the energy crisis, although it will nonetheless see a decline in 2023. Malta does not rely on Russia or Ukraine for a substantial portion of its imports or for considerable tourism revenue. Malta has leveraged its fiscal headroom to significantly insulate people and companies from the effects of the energy shock because it is one of the few eurozone countries that abides by the debt ratio guideline set forth in the Stability and Growth Pact. The state has subsidized the losses of the public utility Enemalta for this policy, which was to freeze retail energy rates at 2014 levels. As a result, Malta has the lowest inflation rate in the eurozone. In addition, with an unemployment rate under 3%, the labor market, which was already constrained before the pandemic, is considerably tighter, which is pushing wages up further. As a result, the effects of inflation on private spending are partially masked. The tourism industry is anticipated to reach or surpass pre-pandemic levels of growth. The IT and tech sector, which includes virtual poker, casino games, sports betting, and database administration, is projected to have a steep fall in growth as a result of the industry\'s global readjustment, but it will still boost service exports, as well as the financial and shipping sectors. Despite the exorbitant cost of imported energy, net exports will contribute positively. The relatively modest NextGenerationEU (NGEU) fund allocation (1.7% of GDP) and the nation\'s efforts to create a business-friendly climate, notably for the tech sector, will help to attract investment. This potential, however, is likely to be constrained by the ongoing threat of criminal consequences tied to alleged money laundering and other illegal acts. '),(70,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' MRU ','Mauritanian Ouguiya','Mauritania','In 2023, Mauritania\'s economic development will continue to be positive. The agriculture sector, which contributes 25% of the GDP and supports roughly 50% of the global population, is undoubtedly influenced by high prices, but it is also affected by the rising global demand for food as a result of population expansion. Additionally, the government can rely on the growth of cattle farming and fisheries, which together account for 25% of exports and help diversify the economy. Additionally, the high level of food prices will encourage the processing of seafood and agricultural raw resources. This suggests that the agri-food industry has significant potential and might draw both domestic and international investors. However, the production of iron ore and gold, whose volumes will rise once more in 2023 despite falling global prices, will continue to be the key drivers of development. The Société Nationale Industrielle Minière (SNIM), which is primarily responsible for mineral production, accounts for over 60% of exports and 15% of GDP. The Greater Tortue Ahmeyim gas field, which is anticipated to start producing in late 2023, would also help the economy. Domestic demand will continue strong, primarily on the strength of consumption, despite consistently rising inflation brought on by the Russian-Ukrainian conflict. The Mauritanian central bank increased interest rates by 200 basis points to 7% in August 2022, although this policy\'s effects are constrained by the flow of money outside of authorized channels.'),(71,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' MUR ','Mauritian Rupee','Mauritius','After experiencing a year of rapid economic growth in 2022, supported by the rebound in tourism (20% of GDP in 2019), growth slowed down in 2023 as a result of the effects of the global economic slowdown, decreased demand in Europe, the island\'s largest market, and restrictive economic policy (especially monetary policy). In 2024, growth is predicted to stabilize and remain comfortable. It will continue to be supported by the tourism industry\'s modest but steady rebound, the improving construction industry, and growth in the manufacturing and financial services sectors. Growth will also be aided by the return of exports, which will account for 50% of GDP in 2022 and primarily consist of apparel (24%), fish products (14%), and sugar (9%). The recovery in the tourism industry, declining unemployment (from a peak of 10.5% in early 2021 to 6.7% in early 2023) and more moderate inflation will continue to support private spending, which will account for 70% of GDP in 2022. After rocketing in 2022 as a result of the skyrocketing worldwide costs for energy and agricultural supplies, which were nearly entirely imported, inflation began to decline in 2023 along with softening prices. The Bank of Mauritius, whose benchmark interest rate increased from 1.85% during the pandemic to 4.5% in June 2023, backed this trend. Monetary policy may be gradually eased in 2024 as expected, following the lead of the FED and the ECB, while the implementation of a new framework in January 2023, which includes, among other things, a 2-5% inflation target, would enhance its delivery. The government will also continue to subsidize some food items and oil in order to strengthen household purchasing power. Additionally, fixed capital investment (19.3% of GDP in 2023) ought to be quite constant in 2024.'),(72,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' MXN ','Mexican Peso','Mexico','In Q1 2023, Mexico\'s growth momentum unexpectedly picked up, rising by a robust 3.7% year-over-year (up from 3.6% YOY in Q4 2022) and 1% quarter-over-quarter (up from 0.6% QOQ in Q4 2022). Since income fundamentals remained favorable (including a robust employment market, remittances from expatriates in the US, and a rising wage bill), the outcome was particularly driven by strong services, including retail. However, activity could gradually slow down over the ensuing quarters, primarily as a result of a weaker US economy, which is anticipated to have an impact on Mexico\'s industrial sector, tourism (which will account for 7% of GDP in 2021), and remittances from overseas workers (which will account for 4% of GDP). In reality, the latter should impede the rise of household consumption (which accounts for 65% of GDP), in addition to continuous historically high inflation (albeit it is marginally decelerating). While the increase of net exports (39% of GDP) will slow as domestic activity slows down in the US (78% of exports are sent there), this effect should be offset by slower import growth. Regarding private investment, Mexico typically benefits from the nearshoring story and manufacturing will continue to be a major foreign investment destination. The government announced tax incentives for businesses to invest in an interoceanic industrial corridor to be developed in the southern isthmus of Tehuantepec in June 2023 in the hope of competing with the Panama Canal. This corridor would connect the Pacific port of Salina Cruz in Oaxaca state with the Gulf coast hub of Coatzacoalcos in Veracruz state. However, domestic policy uncertainty is a potential downside risk for private investments. The latter involves the contentious expropriation of a segment of a privately operated train in the Gulf state of Veracruz in May 2023 in order to advance the government\'s top priority isthmus project.'),(73,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' MNT ','Mongolian Togrog','Mongolia','The slow loosening of Covid-related restrictions at the Chinese border, which limit trade between the two nations and which Mongolia\'s mining sector depends on, has hampered economic growth despite the country\'s full reopening in 2022. As a result, the mining industry, which contributes to almost half of the nation\'s GDP, kept shrinking. With the majority of border restrictions being lifted in 2023, the economy should pick up steam since China accounts for approximately 90% of all exports of products. The construction of two new rail links between the two nations should hasten shipments. The expansion of Oyu Tolgoi, one of the biggest copper and gold mines in the world, should start operations in the first half of 2023 and support mining production after delays brought on by the pandemic and discussions with the Mongolian government. In a worldwide context of energy transition and electric car development, there will be strong demand for copper, which will support demand. Private investment would then increase as a result, continuing its strong expansion trajectory. Private consumption (52% of GDP) will be fueled by household support programs like the Child\'s Money Program and a decreased unemployment rate. Nevertheless, high inflation, which has an impact on real income and purchasing power, will continue to restrain consumer expenditure. Inflationary pressures will persist due to the devaluation of the Mongolian Tögrög (-17% in 2022) and supply interruptions on essential imports as a result of international sanctions against Russia, Mongolia\'s sole source of petroleum. Since August 2021, inflation has been continuously higher than the Bank of Mongolia\'s 4-8% objective, prompting the central bank to start raising its policy rate in January 2022. It increased the rate from a historic low of 6% to 13% by February 2023.\n'),(74,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' MAD ','Moroccan Dirham','Morocco','Economic development should resume in 2023 thanks to a favorable base effect, especially in agriculture, after having been severely hampered by imported inflation and unfavorable weather for agriculture. The 2022–2023 winter\'s abundant precipitation may eliminate yield-related adverse threats. Surge harvests in this industry (30% of the population, 12% of GDP) would increase rural consumption. After a 5% increase in the minimum wage and a 10% increase in the pay of agricultural employees, purchasing power increased in September 2022.\n\nAccording to Coface, foreign trade will have a neutral effect on development in 2023. First, thanks to interest from investors, Morocco should keep expanding its markets in the textile and automotive industries. High fertilizer prices should continue to be the main driver of phosphate export value. After the remaining health measures were abandoned in 2022, the tourism industry will continue to recover. However, European allies are beginning to raise concerns about a downturn. Second, the cost of gasoline imports is anticipated to keep rising in 2023.\n\nInfrastructure-related investments are still being made, but local businesses who are struggling with rising expenses are being cautious. In December 2022, the EBRD announced a fresh loan of EUR 100 million to finish building the deep-water port of Nador West Med on the Mediterranean coast. Through the Mohammed VI Fund and a 2021–2025 Industrialization Acceleration Plan, the government aims to direct investment. The UK organization Chariot and the National Office of Electricity and Drinking Water inked a 10-year supply agreement in December 2022 as a result of the finding of new gas deposits on the Atlantic coast (Anchois 2). Therefore, it is anticipated that resources would mostly be used to meet local needs, putting an end to the demand for Algerian gas as well as imports of liquefied natural gas via Spain. By 2025, the Anchois 1 and 2 fields might be operational. In addition, Stellantis has disclosed a EUR 300 million investment program to increase production at its Kenitra plant.'),(75,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' MMK ','Burmese Kyat','Myanmar','The military took over in February 2021 after alleged fraud in the 2020 legislative elections, which was refuted by all international observers. The National League for Democracy (NLD), the winning party in the elections, was overthrown by the military coup. Aung San Suu Kyi, head of the NDL and recipient of the Nobel Peace Prize, served as state advisor up to that point because constitutional restrictions prevented her from holding the office of president. President Win Myint was the country\'s first civilian leader in more than 50 years when he was chosen in 2018 by a college made up of representatives from both houses of parliament and the military. He was replaced by a supporter of the military after the coup. Aung San Suu Kyi was detained following the coup led by General Min Aung Hlaing, and the military junta found her guilty on numerous counts; at the conclusion of the final trial in January 2023, the sentence was increased to 33 years in prison. Major rallies against the military takeover have resulted in 12,000 people being detained and 2,000 deaths, according to estimates. The military executed four well-known pro-democracy activists in the summer of 2022, reintroducing the death penalty after a long absence.\nThe country was further isolated by this recent incident, which received censure from the world community. The Biden administration and the European Union declared sanctions in the wake of the coup. The majority of nations did not recognize the new leadership, so the United Nations decided to postpone its decision on the country\'s participation in December 2021. The relationship with ASEAN is also being impacted by the political upheaval. Although the latter did suspend Myanmar from membership in the organization, it declared in August 2022 that the country\'s leading generals had been excluded from group meetings. Myanmar\'s close ties to Russia during that nation\'s invasion of Ukraine have further distanced it from the West. Russia serves as the junta\'s primary supply of petroleum and is also its primary source of armaments.'),(76,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' NAD ','Namibian Dollar','Namibia','Strong production of diamonds, gold, and uranium, driven by foreign demand and high prices, will be beneficial to growth. In particular, North American sanctions and major jewelers\' voluntary embargos on Russian diamonds will continue to fuel demand for local diamonds. Due to the actions taken against the Russian diamond corporation ALROSA, which had a roughly 30% market share before the Ukraine conflict, Namibian diamonds now have more chances and are therefore more expensive. The production in 2023 will also grow with the addition of the diamond recovery vessel \"Benguela Gem\" to the Debmarine Namibia fleet in March 2022. The increase in tourism brought on by the bettering of the health situation will also encourage activity. As a result, exports will be supported by tourism and diamonds. However, imports will continue to be hampered by consistently high food and energy prices. Since public investment has historically been a significant engine of development, the relatively limited fiscal headroom and the uncertainties surrounding agricultural production will cast a shadow over the outlook. The vast majority of agricultural production is rain-fed and heavily reliant on the ever-changing weather. The industry will also be struggling due to the high cost of animal feed and fertilizers. The policy rate has already increased by 175 basis points since February 2022, but the peg of the Namibian dollar to the South African rand could result in further tightening against a backdrop of persistently high inflation. Finally, monetary tightening, both locally and globally, could weigh on investment. The impact of inflation on household consumption will persist.'),(77,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' NPR ','Nepalese Rupee','Nepal','Despite a fresh and particularly catastrophic wave in July 2021, Nepal steadily recovered from a collapse in economic activity at the height of the COVID-19 pandemic in the first half of 2020, which forced the transport, tourist, and education sectors to nearly totally shut down. It is anticipated that the economic recovery will last until 2022.\nThe recovery was first driven by wholesale and retail trade, transportation, and financial services, while favorable monsoons increased agricultural productivity. Tourism (10% of GDP) came to a complete halt in 2021. Because of a rebound in the hotel and tourism sectors, services are expected to account for 60% of GDP in 2022. Growth will also be driven by industrial activity, which includes the production of textiles, carpets, cigarettes, and cement, as well as agriculture, which will benefit from government investment programs in irrigation.\nThe ongoing vaccination campaign (by September 2021, 19.5% of the population had received all recommended vaccinations), the improvement in household confidence (bolstered by continued employment aid measures), and the resumed expatriate remittance flows—which are expected to pick up significantly due to an upturn in employment in Qatar and Malaysia, where the majority of Nepalese expats are—will all contribute to the recovery on the demand side. Thanks to government support initiatives, particularly for the industries hardest hit by the crisis, and to relatively low (subsidized) loan rates, private investment, which accounts for 23% of GDP, started to recover in 2021 and should continue. The upcoming months\' political and health uncertainties, however, pose a threat to the recovery. As public investment is a government priority in Nepal, it should increase as well. A national project bank has been established in this regard to enhance the administration and execution of public investments. In order to prioritize those needed by the nation, all projects costing more than NPR 500 million (USD 4 million) will now need to be examined before receiving funding.'),(78,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' EUR ','Euro','Netherlands','Economic growth in 2023 and 2024 should be notably slower after a very robust rebound from the Covid-19 pandemic in 2021 and 2022 that was fueled by high private consumption (mostly for services) and successful international commerce. Due to a decline in European energy prices, private spending in 2023 is unlikely to continue at the same rate as the previous two years, even though the inflation rate noticeably decreased during the year. Since gas is the primary heating source in the Netherlands and 3.5 million households (44%) only have short-term heating contracts (6 months), the translation between energy prices and inflation happens swiftly. A price cap on gas and electricity enacted by the Dutch government in the past also contributed to lower energy costs. The Groningen gas field\'s production has significantly declined and will cease in October 2023. However, by that time, two LNG terminals in Eemshaven and Rotterdam will guarantee the supply of energy. It will be less likely that there would be a natural gas shortage in the winter of 2023–2024 due to full gas storage levels (88% as of late July 2023). This indicates that in 2024, when the basis impacts of the oil crisis will have passed and the impact of continuing high service and food costs should hold the inflation rate at a relatively high level, the inflation rate should even out to between 3.0 and 2.5%. Due to higher collective bargaining agreements, which included salary increases of about 10% for several industries in 2023 and will be reinforced by subsequent minor increases in 2024, household spending power will have improved and is likely to keep growing in 2023 and 2024. Unions have been pushed to demand higher salaries as a result of the persistently low unemployment rate, and this trend should continue. In January 2023, the minimum salary increased by 10%, and in July 2023, it increased by 3.1%. It is anticipated to rise again, albeit more slowly, in January and July 2024. However, given that it has largely depended on a decline in the savings rate in recent years, private spending, which accounts for 43% of GDP, should continue to be restrained. The savings rate for private households dropped to 17.5% in Q2 2023, the lowest level recorded in the time series (which began in Q3 2019). In the first half of 2023, home values fell by 6%, and consumers should be more cautious about making large purchases given the forecast of persistently high borrowing rates. When salaries rise more quickly and significantly in 2024, private consumption should begin to climb once more.'),(79,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' NZD ','New Zealand Dollar','New Zealand','The majority of COVID-related limitations will be lifted in September 2022, but high inflation and rising interest rates will cause the economy to slow down even more in 2023. The second quarter of 2022 saw inflation reach a three-decade high, driven by rising costs for food, energy, and housing. Inflation will be driven by second-round impacts from higher prices the year before even if the rate of price growth will slow in 2023. Consumer confidence, which reached an all-time low in mid-2022, is anticipated to continue to have an impact on household consumption (57% of GDP). Additionally, dropping home prices, slower population growth due to fewer immigration since the pandemic, and high household debt levels (173% of disposable income in Q2 2022) will also restrain private spending growth. The Reserve Bank of New Zealand (RBNZ) began raising interest rates in late 2021 in response to escalating inflation. The policy rate was 4.25% on January 10, 2023, after the central bank adopted a more aggressive stance in response to Russia\'s invasion of Ukraine. It increased the size of increments from 25 bps to 50 bps and subsequently to 75 bps. Since the RBNZ anticipates that inflation will stay high, further increases may be necessary in 2023. The housing market collapse and rising interest rates will have an effect on investment, whose growth is anticipated to decrease. Public investment in infrastructure projects, notably those related to transportation, should increase gross fixed capital formation. As tourism (14% of GDP and 16% of jobs in 2019) progressively recovers after the country authorized fully immunized overseas travelers to enter the country in August 2022, exports of services should increase. The global economic downturn, however, could have an impact on exports of goods because in 2021, China and the US will account for 32.5% and 10.5% of all exports, respectively. Additionally, the danger of a European recession looms large (EU and UK exports made for 8.6% of all products exported in 2021).'),(80,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' NIO ','Nicaraguan Córdoba','Nicaragua','Due to increasing energy prices, tightening US sanctions, and local copying of the FED\'s monetary tightening policies, the economic recovery lost impetus in 2022. In 2023, the tendency is expected to persist. First, the domestic economy will continue to struggle. Increased unemployment (at least 4.7% of the labor force is anticipated by 2023) and persistently high inflation (the Central Bank of Nicaragua\'s inflation objective is between 2% and 4%) will reduce household disposable income. Remittances from US expatriates, whose numbers have significantly increased and accounted for at least 70% of all remittances in 2022, could, however, mitigate the effect. Second, it is anticipated that both public and private underinvestment would intensify. The new FDI restrictions imposed by the Biden administration in 2022 on sugar imports, local authorities, and gold mining will further discourage foreign direct investment and might lead Canadian mining corporations to scale back their operations. The financially strangulated monetary policy (repo rate of 8.87% in October 2022 and projected to average over 7.00% for 2023) will prevent domestic businesses from making investments. Access to bank loans will become even more challenging because of the high percentage of corporate defaults. The public order necessary for building will be further undermined by the state\'s budgetary restraint. Third, weak external demand will once more have an impact on the creation of products and services. The Maquiladoras\' output of beef (11%) and textiles (35% of exports in 2021 go to North and Central America) will decline due to slowing economies in the US (56% of total exports in 2021) and Central America (28%). Despite this, the worldwide demand for commodities like gold, platinum, coffee, and tobacco will keep mining (13% of total exports in 2021) and agricultural output (21% of total exports) from declining, especially given that the rapprochement with China may raise demand.'),(81,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' XOF ','West African Cfa Franc','Niger','The economy of Niger recovered in 2022 after experiencing a year of subpar growth in 2021 as a result of the reduction in agricultural activity—which accounts for 40% of GDP and 80% of the population—caused by insufficient rainfall. If the weather is good, it should continue to be robust in 2023, primarily due to the agriculture industry. The continued building of important infrastructure, such as the China National Petroleum Corporation\'s Niger-Benin pipeline, which will be put into service in the second half of the year to improve oil production, will also support Niger\'s growth. Additionally, the Kandadji dam\'s construction will continue through 2025. Oil industry growth is anticipated to reach 86% after 20.6% in 2022, supported by rising exports and worldwide pricing. Household spending will be supported by the agricultural sector\'s positive development prospects, and private investment will be stimulated by the oil sector\'s expansion. By raising interest rates, the Central Bank of West African States is anticipated to continue achieving its principal goal of containing inflation. However, due to potential rises in the price of agricultural inputs, inflation threats will continue to pose a threat to the agricultural industry.'),(82,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' NGN ','Nigerian Naira','Nigeria','Nigeria\'s economy would continue to benefit from strong oil prices through 2022 but will moderate a bit in 2023. The sturdiness of transportation (2% of GDP) and the quick growth of the digital economy (15% of GDP), despite the nation\'s reliance on oil and gas, will assist growth in other sectors. One of the major ports in West Africa, the new Lekki deepwater port, which opened in January 2023 and is situated 150 kilometers from Lagos, would significantly help Nigerian trade. The Nigeria Start up Act would also benefit the entertainment (music, film, etc.) and information technology (Fin Tech) industries, both of which are seeing rapid growth as a result of the emergence of several start-ups. The legislation, which the government will promulgate in October 2022, offers tax benefits and a fund for innovation. The devastating floods of October 2022 will have an impact on manufacturing (18% of GDP) and agriculture (25% of GDP). When the agricultural sector supports more than 50% of the population and accounts for 50% of jobs, activity will be disrupted by the destruction of crops and certain infrastructure (roads, bridges, etc.). Additionally, the oil industry will continue to play a major role in propelling Nigeria\'s economic growth. Assuming that neither the theft of hydrocarbons nor their covert extraction nor its effects on the economy as a whole are taken into account, its real weight in the economy greatly exceeds its strict contribution to GDP (9%). Trade will favorably impact growth despite the new Dangote mega-refinery\'s delayed start-up, which is intended to increase crude oil production (with a processing capacity of 650,000 b/d) and decrease imports of refined products. Import demand will be impacted by the naira\'s significant depreciation (66% between 9 and 19 June 2023, reaching the level of the parallel market but with sharp fluctuations), which followed the consolidation of foreign exchange windows under the Investors and Exporters (I&E) window and the Central Bank of Nigeria\'s (CBN) adoption of a floating exchange rate in line with the new President\'s program.'),(83,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' KPW ','North Korean Won','North Korea','The country fell into recession in 2020 and 2021 as a result of COVID-19-related severe lockdowns and border closures, harsh weather, and pre-existing UN sanctions over its nuclear weapons program. The borders of North Korea were closed in January 2020. Thereafter, more severe measures were implemented, such as a prohibition on domestic travel, entry restrictions into Pyongyang, the capital, and a 30-day quarantine for anyone exhibiting COVID-19 symptoms. These policies had an impact on services (33.8% of GDP) and the mining and manufacturing sectors (28.1% of GDP in 2020). According to estimates from the Bank of Korea (BOK), the economy would contract by 4.5% in 2020 as a result of historic declines in mining (-9.6%), agriculture (-7.6%), and services (-4.0%). Foreign commerce fell by 67.9% in 2020 compared to the previous year, which was already negatively damaged by the sanctions enacted by the UN Security Council in 2017. The country had switched and significantly increased its exports of watches and wigs before the pandemic, but both collapsed in 2020: -86.3% and -92.7%, respectively, compared to a year earlier. The country\'s main exports, textiles (27% of the total in 2017), coal (22%) and seafood (8%) were already being negatively impacted by UN sanctions. Furthermore, because to isolationism and low income levels before the pandemic, the tourism sector was negatively impacted by border closures. The rising numbers of Chinese visitors in recent years, particularly to Pyongyang, however, helped to sustain it. These patterns ought to have persisted in 2021. '),(84,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' NOK ','Norwegian Krone','Norway','Since the commencement of the conflict in Ukraine, and especially more so since Russia\'s natural gas supply to Germany was cut off (in September 2022), Norwegian gas and oil exports—which made up 60% of all exports in 2021—have been crucial for ensuring the security of Europe\'s energy supply. In 2023, things will stay the same. Although the consumer nations of Europe are exploring for alternatives, such as by building LNG facilities, these initiatives still need some time until the European energy market adjusts to the new circumstances. Early in 2023, when this article was being written, Norway was already supplying Europe with gas at its full capacity. New gas projects are still being constructed, some of which will start operating in late 2022 and others in 2023. Over 53 new production licenses covering the North Sea, Norwegian Sea, and Barents Sea were already given at the beginning of 2022. In the Barents Sea, more licenses will be granted in January 2023. The full installation of a fifth oil mining platform at the Johan Sverdrup oil field should also result in an increase in oil production. About 95% of Norway\'s gas is exported via a vast underwater pipeline network connecting it to terminals in countries like Germany, Britain, France, and Belgium, among others. With the completion of the new Baltic Pipe project, which will transport Norwegian gas from Denmark to Poland, around 60% of Poland\'s former Russian gas imports will be replaced beginning in October 2022. In light of this, the demand for Norwegian energy should stay robust and even rise in the spring, when the natural gas storages are projected to be depleted, notwithstanding a downturn in global economic activity over the winter of 2022–2023. As a result, the overall value of Norwegian exports (about 33% of GDP in 2021) should be supported, as exports from non-oil industries (such as fish, aluminum, manufacturing, and equipment) may suffer as a result of Western Europe\'s slowdown or recession. Despite having a large energy reserve (oil and gas will make up about 27.5% of the energy mix in 2020, with hydropower being the mainstay of the Norwegian electricity system), even for Norwegian consumers and businesses, food and fuel prices have increased significantly, with electricity prices especially rising as a result of low rainfall. This is reducing purchasing power and restricting non-oil investments as well as private spending, which accounts for 45% of GDP.'),(85,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' OMR ','Omani Rial','Oman','Due to increased investment activity (about 25% of GDP) and high hydrocarbon income (35% of GDP), Oman\'s economy will gradually accelerate in 2024. Even though it is predicted that oil production would stop in 2024, increased energy costs will promote economic performance. Additionally, Oman is concentrating more on gas production, which is anticipated to expand 3% yoy to 46 bcm in 2024 following the opening of the Mabrouk North-East Field, as the nation\'s oil reserves are aging. A record high of 16.4 billion cubic meters (bcm) in LNG exports is anticipated in 2024 as a result of debottlenecking efforts (i.e., the completion of the Qalhat LNG terminal\'s extension, which increased capacity by 1 million tonnes annually). The public sector will make the majority of the investments as part of the Vision 2040 program, which aims to diversify the economy. Finance, industry, mining, logistics (mostly including roads and ports), tourism, and digitalization will all benefit from this. The administration has also set a goal of having net zero emissions by 2050. As the authorities prioritize investments in export-oriented sectors like metallurgy, lodging and transportation infrastructure, plastics, petrochemicals, and renewable energy, particularly green hydrogen produced from wind and solar power, greater diversification is anticipated to support net exports\' contribution to growth (around 15% of GDP). A rebound in tourism, ongoing urbanization, and government initiatives to increase the number of Omanis in the workforce—which are centered on substituting trained Omani residents for foreign workers—will all boost private spending, which accounts for around 25% of GDP. The government\'s efforts to gradually reduce expenditure on subsidies will, however, increase inflation in 2024 and impede private consumption. In 2020, Oman declared that water and electricity subsidies would gradually end by 2025.'),(86,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' PKR ','Pakistani Rupee','Pakistan','Pakistan\'s GDP growth is anticipated to moderate in the fiscal year 2023 (FY23, ending 30 June 2023), after expanding rapidly in the two fiscal years prior. This is because efforts to stabilize the economy by addressing fiscal and external imbalances will impose restrictions on economic activity. Over 80% of Pakistan\'s GDP comes from private consumption, which is primarily supported by the country\'s rapid population growth and personal remittances (8.1% of GDP). The loss of income experienced by rural communities, who make up 63% of the total population, as a result of floods that decimated the agricultural sector (20% of GDP) and by rising inflation, which has already been chronically high for several decades, will have an impact on this key development driver in 2023. In 2022, consumer prices spiked sharply as a result of the IMF\'s demands that the economy be stabilized. These included the elimination of a cap on the exchange rate of the Pakistani rupee in January 2023, which led to the currency depreciating sharply, and the withdrawal of the subsidy program, which increased the price of food and petrol. Due to this widening of the inflationary strain, core inflation has been rising at double-digit rates since June 2022. Price pressures will still be severe in 2023, in part as a result of further increases in energy prices that the government imposes in order to increase financial revenues, in line with the IMF\'s request for the complete abolition of energy subsidies. Because to monetary tightness, political risk, stop-and-go economic policies, insufficient structural reform execution, and an underdeveloped banking sector, fixed investment levels have remained low (13% of GDP), and this type of growth is anticipated to remain sluggish.'),(87,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' PAB ','Panamanian Balboa','Panama','In 2022, the economy continued its recovery from the deep recession caused by the Covid-19 pandemic, allowing GDP to exceed its pre-crisis level. The recovery of foreign trade (83% of GDP), exports of goods and services (Canal traffic, re-exports, financial services, copper and gold, tourism) have supported robust growth. Although growth will remain relatively robust in 2023, it is still expected to soften. While household consumption will continue to support activity, inflation will dent it. Support measures introduced in response to the social movements of the summer of 2022, and more particularly the probable continuation of subsidies for basic products (fuel and certain food products), will contain price rises and their impact on spending. Moreover, spending should also be supported by the continuing decline in unemployment despite the post-pandemic recovery in employment  still being incomplete. The rise in US, and therefore Panamanian, interest rates will slow new private investment. However, it should remain supportive of growth, as the country\'s role as a logistics hub and the free trade zones remain conducive to investment. The advantages and incentives for multinational companies put in place by the authorities to establish the country as a nearshoring centre in Latin America could encourage investment in the manufacturing sector. In addition, the government will continue to invest in infrastructure (8% of the budget for 2023) with, for example, projects for a fourth bridge over the canal and a third metro line in Panama City that will support the construction sector (USD 4 billion). The slowdown in world trade will reduce income from re-exports. Logistics services will suffer. However, these revenues will continue to be supported by the rise in mining exports as the production capacity of the Cobre mine, which produced copper and gold, increases.'),(88,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' PGK ','Papua New Guinean Kina','Papua New Guinea','Following a definite uptick in 2023 brought on by the health situation\'s improvement, the economy\'s reopening, and high commodity prices, growth will continue to be robust in 2024, driven mostly by the sector of natural resources. Natural resource exports will continue to grow, with prices for liquefied natural gas (LNG), which makes up more than 25% of all exports, maintaining high due to a finite global supply. The forecast for gold exports is also promising: the Porgera mine, which suspended operations in 2020, is expected to resume operations at the end of 2023, which should increase gold production in 2024. A stronger currency in 2024 is predicted to increase competitiveness, which will benefit other exports. Infrastructure projects, such as the \"Connect PNG\" program (a sizable road transport development plan announced in 2020) and the Papua LNG production site (developed by TotalEnergies, Exxon Mobil, and Santos), whose construction is scheduled to begin in 2024, will be the main drivers of public and private investment. Because to the gradual decline in inflation, fuel and food prices will remain stable. A minor increase in household consumption (which accounts for around 50% of GDP), along with favorable conditions in the extractive and construction industries that will promote job growth and salary increases, will result from decreasing inflation. A continually high poverty rate (approximately 40% in 2022) and the limited influence of other sectors on the agricultural industry, which employs 85% of the population, primarily informally, would nevertheless limit household consumption.'),(89,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' PYG ','Paraguayan Guaraní','Paraguay','In 2023, the resumption of activity should be mainly driven by agriculture (16% of GDP), which in 2022 was strongly affected by severe drought, thereby hampering the sector´s yield (soybean output slumped by 60% in the 2021-2022 crop). The expected improvement in weather conditions will also contribute to a rebound in transport (through higher river water levels) and power generation at hydroelectric plants, thus favouring the utility sector (7% of GDP). Moreover, the aforementioned trends should also lead to a rise in exports despite the expected cooling of global activity (including in its main trade partners Brazil, Argentina, Chile and Russia, in descending order) and some softening of agriculture commodity prices. It is also worth noting that Paraguay only consumes 16% of the energy it produces; the remainder is exported to countries such as Argentina and Brazil, with Paraguay equally sharing the Yacyretá and Itaipú hydroelectric plants on the Parana River with these two respective countries. Household consumption (64% of GDP) should expand, driven by a stronger job market (amid the resumption of domestic activity) and by the gradual easing of inflationary pressures, with both forces prevailing over tighter credit conditions. However, stricter global borrowing conditions should result in tepid growth in gross fixed investments. Private and public investments should be directed primarily to manufacturing and infrastructure, respectively, thereby favouring the construction sector as well. In fact, the government has tried to increase public-private partnerships (PPP), which include the expansion and modernisation of the PY01 route (at an estimated cost of USD 445 million).'),(90,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' PEN ','Peruvian Sol','Peru','In 2023, activity is anticipated to slow down. Although household consumption (which accounts for 66% of GDP) will continue to drive GDP, the rate of expansion will slow. The projection is supported by persistently and historically high inflation, the delayed effects of tighter credit conditions (from an annual minimum of 0.25 percent up until August 2021 to a benchmark interest rate of 7.75 percent in January 2023) and a deteriorating labor market. In contrast, the Con Puche Per economic reactivation plan (estimated at 0.6% of GDP) will aid in slowing the decline in private consumption. The proposal was unveiled in December 2022 in an unsuccessful attempt to stop protests. The plan includes, among other things, steps to increase access to natural gas for households and welfare benefits like pensions. Private investment is expected to continue sluggish, as a result of the tighter local and global financial conditions as well as the unsettling political environment that dampens investor confidence. Similar to private investments, governmental investments ought to perform poorly due to a lack of political emphasis. Last but not least, due to China, Peru\'s largest export market, posting a considerably sharper development momentum, exports (which account for 29% of 2021 GDP), are anticipated to produce a positive but lesser contribution. This may potentially benefit copper prices and subsequently Peru\'s export sales abroad. However, periodic community-led protests at Peruvian mines pose a threat to the red metal\'s exports.'),(91,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' PHP ','Philippine Peso','Philippines','Amidst a complicated local and international context, the Philippines\' economy is anticipated to slow in 2023 after expanding at its strongest rate in more than four decades. The recession in the global economy will have an impact on the nation\'s exports, which will account for 26% of GDP in 2021. Given that the industry provides for over 60% of exports, the sluggish demand for electronics in particular will continue to be a burden. In the United States, private consumption is likewise anticipated to decline as a result of tighter credit and increasing inflation. The latter averaged 5.8% in 2022. Inflation had not reached its peak by January 2023 since it was now affecting a larger spectrum of goods and services. The pattern was further influenced by climatic conditions in the last quarter of 2022, which exacerbated already high food inflation. As a result, in the first month of 2023, both overall inflation and core inflation reached records dating back 14 years and more than two decades, respectively. The Bangko Sentral ng Pilipinas (BSP), the central bank of the Philippines, aggressively reacted to these developments by raising its policy rate by a total of 400 basis points to 6% in February 2023. In the first half of 2023, rate increases are anticipated to continue. A higher savings rate in the last quarter of 2022 (30.5%) may also signal the end of the \"revenge spending\" phenomena that followed the progressive easing of mobility limitations that began in the second quarter of 2022. However, the improvement in the labor market and the rebound in tourism could help underpin household spending, which accounts for 75% of GDP and saw the unemployment rate drop to 4.3% in December 2022 from pre-pandemic levels. Due to the tighter financial circumstances, which have contributed to weakened company confidence, private investment growth is also expected to decline. Despite receiving government assistance, the agriculture sector (10%) will continue to be at risk from extreme weather and high fertilizer prices. A 0.1% drop in agricultural output was recorded in 2022 as a result of storms. Government spending should encourage greater economic expansion in the interim.'),(92,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' PLN ','Polish Złoty','Poland','The Polish economy will develop at one of its slowest rates since its transformation in the late 1980s in 2023. Real household disposable income has been impacted, and the economy has suffered as a result of inflation, which spiked in 2022 and peaked at a high of 17.2% in January 2023. Private spending, which still accounts for 58% of GDP, is essential to the economy. The first quarter of 2023 is predicted to see a peak in inflation, which will then gradually decline but remain significantly above the central bank\'s objective of 2.5% plus a tolerance zone of 1%. The eleven interest rate increases totaling 665 basis points that have been implemented since the monetary tightening cycle began in October 2021, with the most recent one coming in September 2022, may still be ongoing. If tensions are brought on by a stronger labor market that leads to a rebound in household consumption, core inflation developments could trigger further monetary tightening. The labor market is still in good health, with nominal wages growing strongly and the unemployment rate remaining low (2.9% in December 2022, according to Eurostat methodology, and one of the lowest levels in the EU, behind only Czechia and Germany). However, as they entered the negative region and are predicted to remain there as long as double-digit inflation persists and businesses are hesitant to raise their headcounts due to the continued uncertainty, wages have been suffering in real terms.'),(93,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' EUR ','Euro','Portugal','By 2022, the post-pandemic economic recovery had become more robust, allowing GDP to surpass its pre-crisis level right away. In 2023, if the recovery in the tourism industry and private spending are confirmed, the nation will record economic growth that is far higher than that of its European counterparts (the eurozone average is around 1%). Growth should continue to be strong in 2024, but it will slow as the main forces behind the recovery lose their momentum. Private consumption will be negatively impacted by continuously high inflation and its negative effects on consumer purchasing power. Private consumption has previously been supported by the robust labor market and pent-up demand from the pandemic. Furthermore, because nearly 90% of the mortgage stock, which represents more than three-quarters of Portuguese homeowners\' debt, is made up of floating-rate loans, the country\'s consumers are severely impacted by the increase in interest rates. Since the European Central Bank (ECB) is unlikely to start lowering rates again before the second half of 2024, harsher financing conditions will also hurt private investment. Although inflation in Portugal and the rest of the eurozone decelerated in the first half of 2023, the increase in core inflation (i.e., inflation without energy and food) persisted. This softening trend was primarily caused by energy costs. Additionally, 2024 Portuguese exports are forecast to only marginally increase after stalling in 2023 due to the continued weakness of the regional economy. Despite these numerous challenges, the tourism industry, which accounts for 17% of the nation\'s GDP and 50% of service exports in 2019, will continue to be the main driver of activity. But following a spectacular rebound (12% more foreign visitors in the first four months of 2023 than in 2019), activity could increase more slowly in 2024. Additionally, since the nation is one of the primary recipients of European funds, with €13.9 billion in grants under the Recovery and Resilience Plan (RRP), in addition to €2.7 billion in loans, for the period of 2021–2026, public investments in infrastructure, digital transformation, and energy transition will continue to support growth. Although funds are anticipated to be less than in 2023, the year with the highest disbursements, they should nevertheless surpass €3 billion (1.3% of 2022 GDP) in 2024.'),(94,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' QAR ','Qatari Riyal','Qatar','By 2022, the post-pandemic economic recovery had become more robust, allowing GDP to surpass its pre-crisis level right away. In 2023, if the recovery in the tourism industry and private spending are confirmed, the nation will record economic growth that is far higher than that of its European counterparts (the eurozone average is around 1%). Growth should continue to be strong in 2024, but it will slow as the main forces behind the recovery lose their momentum. Private consumption will be negatively impacted by continuously high inflation and its negative effects on consumer purchasing power. Private consumption has previously been supported by the robust labor market and pent-up demand from the pandemic. Furthermore, because nearly 90% of the mortgage stock, which represents more than three-quarters of Portuguese homeowners\' debt, is made up of floating-rate loans, the country\'s consumers are severely impacted by the increase in interest rates. Since the European Central Bank (ECB) is unlikely to start lowering rates again before the second half of 2024, harsher financing conditions will also hurt private investment. Although inflation in Portugal and the rest of the eurozone decelerated in the first half of 2023, the increase in core inflation (i.e., inflation without energy and food) persisted. This softening trend was primarily caused by energy costs. Additionally, 2024 Portuguese exports are forecast to only marginally increase after stalling in 2023 due to the continued weakness of the regional economy. Despite these numerous challenges, the tourism industry, which accounts for 17% of the nation\'s GDP and 50% of service exports in 2019, will continue to be the main driver of activity. But following a spectacular rebound (12% more foreign visitors in the first four months of 2023 than in 2019), activity could increase more slowly in 2024. Additionally, since the nation is one of the primary recipients of European funds, with €13.9 billion in grants under the Recovery and Resilience Plan (RRP), in addition to €2.7 billion in loans, for the period of 2021–2026, public investments in infrastructure, digital transformation, and energy transition will continue to support growth. Although funds are anticipated to be less than in 2023, the year with the highest disbursements, they should nevertheless surpass €3 billion (1.3% of 2022 GDP) in 2024.'),(95,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' RON ','Romanian Leu','Romania','The Romanian economy is expected to slow down in 2023 as a result of rising inflation, tighter financial conditions, and the effects of the Russian-Ukrainian war, despite 2022\'s strong economic growth being driven by private consumption and investments. The immediate repercussions of the Russian-Ukrainian conflict are minimal because the nation exports grains (such as corn, wheat, and barley) and is generally self-sufficient in terms of its energy supply (around 70% of domestic energy production meets local demand). Thanks to purchases from other nations including Kazakhstan, Iraq, Azerbaijan, and the UAE, the already meager energy imports from Russia (particularly crude oil) were greatly decreased. Furthermore, Black Sea Oil & Gas (an independent energy business) started to harvest gas from Romania\'s offshore deposits in June 2021 as a result of regulatory constraints for natural gas extraction from the Black Sea being loosened. However, the rise in global commodity prices is making the indirect effects of the war noticeable.  The latter caused Romania\'s average annual inflation rate to increase in 2022 to over 13.5%, the highest level since 2003, the previous time the country saw a spike in inflation. Inflation has reduced private household purchasing power, which is likely to restrict consumption over the winter and spring of 2022–2023 despite strong public support meant to mitigate its impact. Even while the labor market is slowly improving, the unemployment rate is still higher than it was before the pandemic. Contrarily, skill shortages and brain drain continue to be problems, which may encourage workers to demand higher pay even though the minimum wage should increase. Over 2023, consumer prices are anticipated to rise again, albeit more slowly. The central bank of Romania (NBR) raised its benchmark interest rates to 7% in phases between October 2021 and early 2023 to combat inflationary pressures, driving up borrowing costs to their highest level since February 2010. Depending on the trajectory of inflation, additional increases are anticipated in 2023. Construction investment will be affected by rising interest rates. As a result of the European economic slowdown (more than 73% of trade is within the EU), particularly in Germany (21% of Romanian exports), net exports should once more contribute negatively to growth in 2023. The exports of electrical parts, telephones, machinery, and motor cars and parts (which make up 35% of exports) will struggle in contrast to the strong exports of services and grains, especially in light of supply-chain disruptions and increased unpredictability. Additionally, the relatively strong domestic demand and high energy prices will maintain the high import bill.'),(96,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' RUB ','Russian Ruble','Russia','Despite the milder-than-expected contraction in 2022, the Russian economy is predicted to stay in recession in 2023. Successful financial stabilization initiatives successfully masked the effects of Western sanctions. One of these was the central bank\'s decision to gradually cut interest rates from 20.0% to 7.50% in September 2022 after raising them from 9.5% to 20.0% shortly after the invasion of Ukraine. Holding onto its huge foreign exchange reserves was another aspect of safeguarding the Russian financial system. In February 2023, these reserves, which are under the control of the Russian central bank, totaled USD 589 billion; over half of this amount is frozen as a result of sanctions. However, there is still USD 300 billion available for conceivable currency and debt market interventions. Russian banks appear to be able to function utilizing alternative channels while being denied access to the SWIFT money transfer system, allowing them to communicate with the outside world. Additionally, the ruble stabilized after experiencing sudden changes and was 3.5% stronger by mid-February 2023 compared to its average January 2022 level. This accomplishment is credited to swiftly implemented capital controls as well as declining trading volumes and current account dynamics. Despite the voluntary reduction in gas exports and the oil embargo imposed by EU members, the rise in oil and gas prices as well as the redirection of energy exports to non-sanctioned countries helped to record energy export income. As a result, during this initial phase, the sanctions did not significantly harm the Russian economy. However, their impact has been growing steadily in size, and in the longer future, it will hurt more. Russia\'s overall reliance on imports is small, but several industries, particularly those producing food, chemicals, transportation equipment, and IT services, are particularly vulnerable. Despite efforts to locate alternatives in other nations, such as China, Belarus, and Turkey, as well as in allowing parallel imports, i.e., imports of various goods without the consent of the brand owner, the restricted access to Western inputs caused by sanctions has taken a toll on them. However, sanctions-affected industries have seen significant decreases. The output of automobiles in particular has decreased as a result of foreign businesses leaving Russia. A decrease in airfreight has been caused by import restrictions, the exclusion of Russian carriers from Western airspace, and their isolation from Western replacement parts and services (including leasing). Passenger transportation has decreased significantly less as a result of government subsidies and programs to promote domestic tourism.'),(97,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' SAR ','Saudi Riyal','Saudi Arabia','Despite the milder-than-expected contraction in 2022, the Russian economy is predicted to stay in recession in 2023. Successful financial stabilization initiatives successfully masked the effects of Western sanctions. One of these was the central bank\'s decision to gradually cut interest rates from 20.0% to 7.50% in September 2022 after raising them from 9.5% to 20.0% shortly after the invasion of Ukraine. Holding onto its huge foreign exchange reserves was another aspect of safeguarding the Russian financial system. In February 2023, these reserves, which are under the control of the Russian central bank, totaled USD 589 billion; over half of this amount is frozen as a result of sanctions. However, there is still USD 300 billion available for conceivable currency and debt market interventions. Russian banks appear to be able to function utilizing alternative channels while being denied access to the SWIFT money transfer system, allowing them to communicate with the outside world. Additionally, the ruble stabilized after experiencing sudden changes and was 3.5% stronger by mid-February 2023 compared to its average January 2022 level. This accomplishment is credited to swiftly implemented capital controls as well as declining trading volumes and current account dynamics. Despite the voluntary reduction in gas exports and the oil embargo imposed by EU members, the rise in oil and gas prices as well as the redirection of energy exports to non-sanctioned countries helped to record energy export income. As a result, during this initial phase, the sanctions did not significantly harm the Russian economy. However, their impact has been growing steadily in size, and in the longer future, it will hurt more. Russia\'s overall reliance on imports is small, but several industries, particularly those producing food, chemicals, transportation equipment, and IT services, are particularly vulnerable. Despite efforts to locate alternatives in other nations, such as China, Belarus, and Turkey, as well as in allowing parallel imports, i.e., imports of various goods without the consent of the brand owner, the restricted access to Western inputs caused by sanctions has taken a toll on them. However, sanctions-affected industries have seen significant decreases. The output of automobiles in particular has decreased as a result of foreign businesses leaving Russia. A decrease in airfreight has been caused by import restrictions, the exclusion of Russian carriers from Western airspace, and their isolation from Western replacement parts and services (including leasing). Passenger transportation has decreased significantly less as a result of government subsidies and programs to promote domestic tourism.'),(98,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' XOF ','West African Cfa Franc','Senegal','Although the economy fared reasonably well during the pandemic, the effects of the war in Ukraine have been devastating. The nation depends significantly on foreign sources of food and energy, which will cause substantial import inflation in 2022. Unusually, riots have forced the government to reconsider consumer subsidies. The energy sources of inflation are predicted to drop in 2023, but how much will depend on the climatic risks to agriculture.\nWith the continuation of the \"Emerging Senegal\" Plan, public investment continues to be a growth-promoting factor. The country\'s development has been greatly aided by infrastructure improvements, with average growth of 5% between 2014 and 2019. The deep-water port of Ndayane, set to open in 2022 to ease congestion in the capital (USD 1.1 billion, 60% of which is being provided by the UAE group DP World), phase 1 of the Grand-Tortue Ahmeyim gas and Sangomar oil fields in 2023, and the regional express train between Dakar and the new Blaise Diagne airport have all recently or will soon be put into service.'),(99,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' RSD ','Serbian Dinar','Serbia','Due to consistently high inflation, decreased demand from Serbia\'s main trading partners in Europe, and rising borrowing rates that will weigh on consumption, exports, and private investment, the Serbian economy is predicted to continue to deteriorate in 2023. The Serbian economy is only little directly impacted by the Russia-Ukraine conflict because 5.3% of Serbia\'s imports and 4.9% of its exports of commodities are from Russia. Serbia is the only nation in Europe to hold off on imposing sanctions on Russia despite having denounced the invasion of Ukraine\'s territorial sovereignty and supporting a UN resolution calling for the withdrawal of Russian military. However, because of greater costs associated with production and shipping, the indirect effect of the war, which manifested in substantially higher energy prices in the European market, has expanded to the prices of food and other items. As a result, Serbia\'s annual inflation rate increased to an average of almost 12% in 2022, which is the greatest inflation rate since Serbia was affected by the financial crisis in 2008–2009. Consumer spending should slow down even further over the winter and spring of 2022–2033, as price conflicts are reducing consumers\' purchasing power. Although at a slower rate than in 2022, it is anticipated that consumer prices will rise further in 2023. The National Bank of Serbia (NBS) increased its policy rate eight times by a total of 350 basis points to 4.5% by late 2022 in order to stabilize inflation expectations. In 2023, additional interest rate increases are anticipated. As borrowing costs have increased, rising interest rates have already had a negative impact on private investment and will continue to do so. Government expenditure is projected to provide modest assistance for consumers and businesses to deal with rising energy prices. The minimum wage will also probably rise in 2023 because the labor market is still in rather good shape. Given that import growth is outpacing export growth, net exports\' contribution to GDP growth should continue to be positive but mild.'),(100,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' SLL ','Sierra Leonean Leone','Sierra Leone','After a year in 2022 that was already hampered by the Russian-Ukrainian conflict\'s inflationary effects and severe flooding, Sierra Leone\'s growth should essentially maintain steady in 2023 before picking up in 2024. Due to the high prices of iron ore, titanium, and aluminum, which together make up 70% of the nation\'s exports, export profits will aid in this recovery. With the increase in iron ore production at the Tonkolili and Marampa mines, as well as the government\'s distribution of equipment and rice seed, the mining and agricultural sectors will both continue to recover in 2023 and 2024. Nevertheless, the effects of the severe floods of 2022 are anticipated to continue to harm the agricultural sector in 2023, which is expected to account for 57% of GDP and two-thirds of jobs in 2021 and hence provide a living for a significant portion of the population. The significant depreciation of the leone (67.3% year over year at the end of 2022) will also cause inflation to increase further in 2023 after trending high in 2022. By increasing demand, the larger-than-anticipated increase in government spending on food and energy subsidies has also served to drive up inflation. Inflation will still be fueled by rising import food and fuel costs in 2023. Additionally, as Sierra Leone buys most of its rice from Asian nations, the El Nio phenomenon is anticipated to have a detrimental effect on those nations\' harvests, further driving up food costs. After the elections, the new government\'s actions to tighten fiscal policy, which should reduce consumer consumption, are likely to cause inflationary pressures to relax slightly in 2024. The pressures caused by inflation will also be reduced by tighter monetary conditions. In order to battle growing prices and the depreciation of its currency, the central bank is anticipated to maintain the increase in its key rate that started in early 2022 (19.25% in July 2023 compared to 14% in January 2022). The \"new leone,\" which will enter circulation in March 2023, will also replace the current currency at a rate of 1 for 1000 in 2023, regaining the trust of the populace in the local currency.'),(101,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' SGD ','Singapore Dollar','Singapore','As Singapore continues to treat COVID-19 as an endemic disease and reopens its borders, the country\'s economic recovery will broaden. After a strong recovery in 2021, we anticipate a moderated GDP growth rate in 2022, although it is still expected to be above trend. Given its substantial reliance on foreign trade, Singapore\'s economy will gain from still robust external demand, albeit to a lesser extent than initially anticipated. The conflict in Ukraine and the ensuing sanctions have an impact on global consumption and worsen already tight supply conditions, which has an impact on international trade even though Singapore does not have close economic relations to Russia or Ukraine. Additionally, China\'s strict COVID policy raises dangers.\n\nNevertheless, the manufacturing sector (>20% of GDP) should be supported by the dynamic demand for electronic goods, as well as for machinery and transport equipment, which combined account for approximately half of all domestic exports (merchandise exports minus re-exports). Along with the pharmaceutical business, the info-communications and financial sectors (almost 20% of GDP) will continue to have strong growth in the COVID age. The cost of materials should continue to rise, and there should be a labor scarcity. Despite the easing of border controls and internal COVID containment measures, private investment (which accounts for around 25% of GDP) may be limited by weakened business confidence in the face of geopolitical unpredictability, a slowing global economy, and rising inflation that affects input costs.'),(102,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' EUR ','Euro','Slovakia','The invasion of Ukraine by Russia, as well as the subsequent EU sanctions and US retaliatory measures, have significantly altered Slovakia\'s economic outlook. Natural gas and oil make up a sizable portion of Slovakia\'s energy mix (27% and 25%, respectively, in 2021). In 2021, Slovakia purchased all of its oil and 87% of its natural gas from Russia. There is an immediate possibility that Slovakia\'s energy supplies to Russia could be stopped given that Slovakia is actively backing Ukraine, with which it shares a 97km-long border. The nation still had enough reserves to survive through the 2022–2023 winter without importing Russian gas thanks to its reasonably full gas storage (as of mid–January 2023, storage capacity was still 73% full). The proposed gas interconnector between Poland and Slovakia, which can supply Slovakia with LNG from the ports on the Baltic Sea, will be one of the alternative sources until 2023. Even Norwegian gas might be delivered to Slovakia via the Baltic Pipe that connects the Polish and Danish gas networks. However, it is unlikely that these sources could offset the Russian deliveries. Slovakia might use the Adria pipeline to import oil from Saudi Arabia and other Middle Eastern nations for its oil needs, but the Slovak refineries would need to be modified because they are currently unable to process this \"light\" crude oil. Despite the fact that Slovakia\'s energy supply is secure, at least for the foreseeable future, high European energy costs have had a direct impact on Slovakia\'s inflation rate. After the conflict began, inflation spiked rapidly and peaked in June 2022 at 13% to 15%, which was its highest level since 1999. Given that regulated household energy prices climbed significantly in January 2023, price pressure is only anticipated to slightly diminish before the end of 2023. Even though the minimum wage was raised that same month by 8.4% to €700 per month, real wages will still decline significantly, lowering consumer purchasing power. The future of corporate investments is quite uncertain and is dependent on the business plan adopted by the corporations, who may decide to delay their investments in response to rising interest rates. The future for the automotive industry, which accounts for 13.9% of GDP and 36% of the nation\'s exports, is also a factor in the investment outlook. Disruptions in the supply chain caused by both semi-conductors and the war in Ukraine last year have hurt the industry.'),(103,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' ZAR ','South African Rand','South Africa','Despite a slowdown in economic activity in 2022, it still marginally beat forecasts, largely because of the durability of the agricultural and banking sectors. The current energy crisis, which is a result of the mismanagement of the state-owned power firm Eskom, has significantly deteriorated the outlook, though. President Cyril Ramaphosa proclaimed a \"state of national disaster\" in February 2023 despite efforts to alleviate the problem. In spite of this, load-shedding has dramatically increased over the previous five years and is predicted to get worse in 2023, when there will likely be 200 full days of cuts as opposed to 157 in 2022 and 22 in 2019. The economy will be affected broadly by this, with electricity-intensive industries including mining, paper, metals, and retail being the most impacted. Additionally, the primary drivers (fuel, food, and power) will continue to be high through most of 2023, despite the fact that inflation, which peaked at 7.8%, is steadily declining. Given the lack of investor confidence, a weaker rand is likely to increase the cost of imported products, especially food. The high unemployment rate (over 30%) and inflation will have an adverse effect on household disposable income and, consequently, on consumption (which accounts for 66% of GDP). The South African Reserve Bank increased its benchmark repo rate by 425 bps since November 2021, to 7.75% as of April 2023, in an effort to reduce inflationary pressures. Interest rates will stay high, preventing investment growth, even though the rate of rate increases is probably going to taper down in 2023. However, given the public infrastructure projects being planned, particularly in the areas of transportation, logistics, water, and sanitation, it is anticipated to remain favorable. The contribution of net exports will continue to be negative in 2023 as a higher reduction in exports, brought on by weaker demand from major export markets (China, EU, US), as well as production capacity restrictions, will more than offset the decline in imports brought on by lower domestic consumption. However, exports might still gain if China experiences a robust resurgence in the latter part of the year. The country\'s exposure to climate risks is still very high, and the frequency of extreme events—like the floods in April 2022 and February 2023—is increasing. If these events come to pass, they could have a significant impact on the outlook due to potential disruptions to transportation networks and impacts on the agricultural industry.'),(104,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' KRW ','South Korean Won','South Korea','The growth momentum in 2022 is anticipated to decline as the economic benefit from normalizing business conditions starts to wane, with South Korea\'s GDP projected to surpass its pre-pandemic level in 2021. With exports accounting for about 40% of GDP and serving as the major engine of development, the economy will continue to rely heavily on exports, particularly as long as high-tech goods from Korea are in high demand. The demand for electronics and semiconductors is likely to remain strong globally throughout the year, although export growth may be hampered by a protracted supply chain disruption. The expansion of exports should encourage additional facility and construction spending (23% of GDP in 2019). The manufacturing sector (26% of GDP in 2019) will continue to prosper in this environment. As the nation tries to make the transition into a \"living with COVID\" approach for the long-term and reopen the economy despite rising immunization, the rebound in private spending (48% of GDP in 2019) should continue beyond 2022. Early in January 2022, South Korea has fully immunized more than 80% of its population, with more than 40% receiving booster injections. Household spending will be further boosted by improving labor market conditions, particularly if the labor participation rate begins to increase amid improving growth expectations. Although the participation rate remained below its pre-pandemic level in August 2021, the unemployment rate (without accounting for seasonality) fell to an eight-year low of 2.6%, signifying a net exodus of workers from the labor force. High household debt (household debt-to-disposal income ratio at a record 92.8% in Q2 2021) in a rising interest rate environment will be the main danger to the outlook for private expenditure.'),(105,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' EUR ','Euro','Spain','Spain was severely impacted by the COVID-19 epidemic because of its reliance on the tourism industry (12% of GDP and 13% of jobs), but its recovery momentum has drastically deteriorated since the start of the crisis in Ukraine. The GDP won\'t reach its pre-crisis level in 2023 since the environment will still be unfavorable. Despite a recovery in 2022, there were 15% fewer international tourists than in 2019 and tourism was 15% below pre-pandemic levels.  Spain, however, is less dependent on Russian gas than other European nations and gets the majority of its supplies from the US and Algeria. Additionally, it is less vulnerable to the possibility of a supply disruption due to its geographical isolation and low level of gas connection with the rest of the continent. Given that the nation has multiple infrastructures (6 terminals) for importing liquefied natural gas, this is much more true. Due to its current isolation, the nation can also take advantage of more favorable prices on the MIBGAS market (with Portugal). Additionally, the government has been permitted to control the price of gas used in electricity generation starting in mid-2022 and lasting through May 2023 according to a \"Iberian derogation\" given by the European Commission. Thus, inflation should keep falling as a result of the decrease in gas and electricity prices toward the end of 2022. However, because the increase in energy prices has spread to other goods and services, core inflation will continue to be higher than it was before the crisis, reaching 7% in December 2022. The purchasing power of households will decrease as salaries grow more slowly. Households will cut back on consumption since the current state of unpredictability encourages precautionary savings.'),(106,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' LKR ','Sri Lankan Rupee','Sri Lanka','A major debt and balance of payments problem in Sri Lanka resulted in a sovereign default in May 2022. In April 2022, the government declared that it would stop making payments on its foreign debt and has hired financial and legal advisors to help it with debt restructuring. Depleted reserves caused restrictions on foreign exchange liquidity, which led to acute shortages of food, fuel, medication, and other necessities. Following commitments of funding from significant bilateral creditors like Japan, India, and China, which together hold 83.5% of the country\'s total external debt, Sri Lanka turned to the IMF for urgent assistance. The country and the IMF Board came to an agreement on a 4-year, USD 2.9 billion extended fund facility program on March 20, 2023.\n\nFiscal restraint, a dearth of foreign exchange reserves, and supply constraints were among the causes that caused Sri Lanka\'s economy to enter a severe recession in 2022. These same factors will continue to have a significant impact on economic activity in 2023. Due to reduced income and job opportunities as a result of the economy\'s severe decline in 2022, private consumption, which accounts for 63% of GDP, will have a negative impact on economic growth. 30% of the workforce is employed in the agricultural sector, which will be particularly hard hit because some farmers have been forced to scale back or abandon their operations due to declining yields brought on by the temporary suspension of imports of chemical fertilizers and pesticides in 2021, which will be followed by price increases in the wake of the war in Ukraine.  In addition, because of persistently high commodity prices and high global energy and food prices, private consumption will inadvertently suffer. In 2023, inflation will also continue to be high. Additionally, the low level of public and private investment will not contribute to an increase in economic activity. Tight fiscal policies will limit public spending, and the bleak economic outlook will have a negative influence on private investment, which has already been hit by a reduction in the total stock of credit available to the private sector. Last but not least, net imports will help Sri Lanka\'s economy grow despite a slowdown in its main export markets (the United States, the United Kingdom, etc.). Net imports will decrease as a result of the dual effects of import compression brought on by a lack of foreign currency and the ongoing recovery of exports of apparel, food, and travel. However, supply-side restrictions (regular power outages, protracted input shortages, transportation issues disrupting supply chains, etc.) will continue to have an impact on merchandise exports, while tourism, which should benefit from the reopening of China\'s borders, will suffer from the violent images of social unrest in 2022.'),(107,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' SDG ','Sudanese Pound','Sudan','For the past four years, political unrest and demonstrations have afflicted Sudan. A \"Sovereign Transitional Council\" made up of civilians and soldiers was put in place in 2019 following widespread demonstrations and the army\'s overthrow of Islamist President Omar al-Bashir, who had been in charge since 1989. General Abdel Fattah al-Burhane, the country\'s president, dissolved the interim government in October 2021, expelled the Sovereign Transitional Council from its pro-civilian bloc, imprisoned Prime Minister Abdallah Hamdok, proclaimed a state of emergency, and suspended the constitution\'s power-sharing charter. The military feared (as it still does now) losing its economic interests and facing legal action for its atrocities against the populace. The Popular Resistance Committees, who are leading the 2019 revolution, and the Coalition of Forces for Freedom and Change, which consists of political parties and associations, are calling for the military to leave politics in response to this. Sudan appears to be locked in a political impasse as the military continues to suppress civilian rallies, betting on the movement\'s weariness. Sudan was paralyzed by protests throughout 2022. On December 5, 2022, the Coalition and the military signed a new (preliminary) agreement. This agreement lays out the fundamentals for the reinstatement of a transitional civilian government, a two-year transition period, elections, and the administrative takeover of military-owned businesses. The road to a negotiated transition, however, appears to be difficult. The Vice Squad\'s return represents a surrender to the Islamists who were driven from power by the 2019 revolution, while the popular resistance committees, who were contesting the legitimacy of the Coalition, kept up their mobilization after the agreement was made public.'),(108,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' SEK ','Swedish Krona','Sweden','The Swedish economy is anticipated to decline in late winter 2022 and into early spring 2023 due to rising inflation after an episode of strong growth in the first half of 2022, driven by robust private consumption and investment. Sweden imported just 1% from Russia and exported just 1.3% to it, indicating that the Russian invasion of Ukraine had a negligible direct impact. Instead, decreased energy supplies, supply chain concerns, and export restrictions have been the main effects of the Russia-Ukraine conflict, which have raised prices around the world, particularly for food and energy. As a result, Sweden\'s average annual inflation rate in 2022 increased to almost 8.3%, which was the highest level since 1991. Private expenditure is anticipated to decline over the spring months as a result of price pressures that are reducing household purchasing power. Despite compensation talks in March 2023, lower buying power is unlikely to be made up for by increased salaries. The Riksbank will raise its policy rate in 2023, but in smaller steps than in 2022, when it increased by 250 basis points to 2.5%, as consumer prices will rise more but at a slower rate than in 2022. Since the majority of real estate mortgages in Sweden have variable interest terms, the sharply rising interest rates have also been problematic for private homebuilders. Home prices have been falling since the beginning of 2022 as fewer individuals can afford them. Construction expenses have recently increased significantly as a result of labor and material shortages. Therefore, throughout 2023, construction activity should stabilize or even decline. Additionally, there will be a minor decline in positive international trade. Due to problems with the supply chain and a decline in external demand, goods exports should grow more slowly. Private investment should decelerate in the first half of 2023 despite aggressive state support measures like fuel tax reductions, unemployment compensation, and local government subsidies. However, funding from the EU Recovery and Resilience Facility, which is anticipated to include payments totaling about 0.2% of GDP, will assist initiatives connected to climate change.'),(109,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' CHF ','Swiss Franc','Switzerland','Compared to its Western European neighbors, the Swiss economy has been more resilient in 2023 and has a slightly brighter outlook for 2024. One notable distinction is that Switzerland\'s private consumption is comparatively strong, supported by a number of reasons. Energy price pressures were lower than in many other Western European nations in recent years because of the country\'s considerable reliance on nuclear and renewable energy sources (particularly hydropower). The Swiss Franc\'s strength helped keep imported inflation at a low level. As a result, despite pressures from the real estate market to the upside, the Swiss inflation rate slipped below the Swiss National Bank\'s (SNB) objective of 2% in June 2023 and is projected to stay there. The Swiss government increased the mortgage reference interest rate (\"hypothekarischer Referenzzinssatz\") from 1.25 to 1.5% in June 2023, but the full impact won\'t be felt until the following autumn. Additionally, because landlords can pass along 40% of the inflation gain to their tenants, rents would rise even more. The mortgage reference interest rate should not change in 2024. Wages are anticipated to expand faster than inflation in 2024 than they did in 2023, leading to positive real wage growth. However, a fast increase in population as a result of the highest level of immigration in the past 15 years has a significant impact on private consumption. Population growth of 1.4% in 2023 and 1.2% in 2024, according to the University of Zürich, is substantially higher than the average of 0.8% over the previous three years. This will boost employment and enhance consumption in Switzerland, where the labor market is still extremely tight.'),(110,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' TWD ','New Taiwan Dollar','Taiwan','Since Taiwan\'s economy is heavily export-oriented and plays a significant role in the global electronics value chain, it continues to benefit from the pandemic\'s strong global demand for goods. Between January and October 2021, merchandise exports—which made up 54% of the GDP in 2019—rose by 30% from a year earlier, accounting for 57% of the 6.7% GDP growth rate during that time period. The increase in domestic investment in manufacturing capacity, expansion, replacement, and productivity was a result of the export boom, particularly in technology (ICT, electronics items). During the first three quarters of 2021, gross capital investment increased by 20%.\nAlthough slower than in 2021, we anticipate Taiwan to continue its robust export growth in 2022, which will boost investment. However, given that expanding supply capacity, particularly in semiconductor fabrication, needs time in the face of a high and persistent demand, Taiwan\'s technology exports may be limited in their ability to grow if supply conditions remain tight for an extended period of time.\nDue to better employment conditions and the quintuple stimulus vouchers (worth USD 5.8 billion), private consumption, which accounts for 52% of 2019 GDP, should pick up in 2022. Further economic liberalization and a relaxing of border controls should help revitalize the tourism industry (4.4% of 2019 GDP) once at least 70-80% of the populace has received all recommended vaccinations. Just over 70% of the population has taken two doses by the beginning of January 2022. As benefits from a low base effect fade, the growth momentum of the Taiwanese economy is anticipated to decline overall in 2022. In the meantime, inflation, which had increased in 2021 as a result of rising energy and food prices, could somewhat decline in 2022.'),(111,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' TJS ','Tajikistani Somoni','Tajikistan','Contrary to all predictions, Tajikistan\'s economy remained robust in 2022. Close ties to Russia ultimately aided growth; as a result of increased Russian defense orders and the mobilization of domestic workers, the number of Tajik workers in Russia climbed by 51.8% over the course of the year. The growth in remittances that followed the rouble\'s appreciation, the influx of Russian migrants and their capital, as well as all of these factors together have considerably fueled household consumption (+14.5% year over year in 2022). However, when workers\' remittances, which make up 37% of GDP and primarily come from Russia, run out of steam, economic development is predicted to decrease in 2023 and 2024. Remittances, which are frequently the primary source of income for households, would be negatively impacted by the declining demand for foreign workers in Russia amid the standstill in the Ukraine war. Net imports will have a similar detrimental effect on growth. The nation, which is a net importer of oil, would suffer from persistently high oil prices globally and the decline in the prices of its small export market, which consists primarily of gold and aluminum. Despite these challenges, public investment will be the primary driver of economic growth, with the government depending on a select number of major infrastructure projects to spur the economy and add jobs. One of them, the Rogoun hydropower project, started in 2016 and is scheduled to be finished in 2029, intends to construct the tallest dam in the world, which will be able to generate as much electricity as three nuclear reactors. Additionally, monetary easing could spur growth in the private sector\'s investment, which is still in its infancy (13% of formal employment, 15% of overall investment, and 30% of industrial production). The National Bank of Tajikistan (NBT) recently loosened its monetary policy by lowering its main benchmark rate by 100 basis points to 10% in May 2023 in an effort to spur investment and growth. The release of the nation\'s strategic food reserves, a decline in commodity prices, and a 2.6% increase in the value of the somoni against the dollar all contributed to the reduction in interest rates, which came after a cumulative increase of 275 basis points between January 2021 and August 2022.'),(112,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' TZS ','Tanzanian Shilling','Tanzania','The economy has to deal with the impact of the war in Ukraine, particularly on prices, after demonstrating relative resilience in the face of the Covid-19 outbreak thanks to gold exports (40% of the total) and the authorities\' failure to impose significant health restrictions. Nevertheless, despite the predicted slowdown in growth, it should still be strong because of present and upcoming infrastructure projects\' public and private investment. For instance, it is anticipated that the standard gauge railroad project will proceed. Beginning in late 2019, construction on the railway line will connect the nation with Rwanda and Uganda, followed by Burundi and the Democratic Republic of the Congo. The Ministry of Public Works and Transport plans to invest USD 1.7 billion on projects to develop transportation infrastructure, including this one. The purchase of four new Boeing aircraft by Air Tanzania is also budgeted for expenditure. According to the deal reached with Shell (UK) and Equinor (Norway), the USD 30 billion offshore natural gas production and liquefaction project is anticipated to get underway in 2023. However, as the final investment decision is not anticipated until 2025, the impact on GDP will be minimal in the short term. In contrast, as a result of the conflict in Ukraine, the terms of trade are deteriorating and the cost of imports is rising. While capital goods needed for infrastructure projects will continue to boost imports, the rise in fuel and food costs, along with disruptions to the fertiliser and pesticide markets, will reduce trade\'s ability to contribute to GDP. Furthermore, the decline in visitor numbers from Ukraine and Russia (11% of arrivals in 2021) is anticipated to have an adverse impact on tourism revenues, which were already battling to return to their pre-crisis level. The cost of imported items is also growing, as are commodity costs, driving inflation to its highest level since 2017, which will reduce the contribution of private spending. Nevertheless, the central bank\'s 5% objective for inflation is not expected to be reached, and the announced elimination of the mobile money levy will increase consumer spending power.\n'),(113,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' THB ','Thai Baht','Thailand','In 2023, Thailand\'s economic development is anticipated to pick up speed, enabling real GDP to surpass its pre-pandemic (2019) level for the first time. Due to the removal of internal and international mobility constraints, the tourism-related industries will keep growing. While this proportion was only 0.6% in 2021, international visitor arrivals during the January–November period in 2022 were 25% more than those reported during the same time in 2019. The reopening of Chinese borders should also help the tourism industry in 2023 because, before the pandemic, China accounted for the largest share of all foreign visitors (27.6% of the total in 2019). Recovery in the tourism industry will aid in the expansion of the labor market, which will promote private spending (55% of GDP in 2021). The unemployment rate decreased from a 16-year high of 2.3% in the third quarter of 2021 to 1.2% in the same period of 2022, even though it remained higher than in 2019, when it averaged 1%. From a 14-year peak in 2022, inflation is predicted to sharply drop, relieving the burden on private consumption. In that sense, the Bank of Thailand implemented three increases of 25 basis points in 2022, which was a reasonably gradual rate of monetary tightening. In the first half of 2023, the Thai central bank is anticipated to keep raising interest rates. Any move toward monetary tightening could have an adverse effect on household expenditure, which is already constrained by a high level of debt (86.8% as of the third quarter of 2022). Private investment should be strong despite rising interest rates during an economic recovery.  However, other businesses that are focused on exports, like electronics, may suffer from global headwinds. Public infrastructure spending, particularly the high-speed railway project connecting Bangkok and Nong Khai, on the border with Laos, will be what drives public investment in the meanwhile.'),(114,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' TND ','Tunisian Dinar','Tunisia','A dysfunctional parliamentary system that saw conflicts between the President, Prime Minister, and Parliament has been replaced by an ultra-presidential dictatorship ten years after the 2011 revolution. President Kas Saed took over the judiciary at the end of July 2021 and began enforcing his institutional agenda after being elected in October 2019. He suspended Parliament, removed the Prime Minister, and gradually changed the institutional landscape. A system centered on the President was passed by a constitutional vote in July 2022, and local powers with consistently hazy mandates were created. Two rounds of early legislative elections were held between December 2022 and January 2023, although only a relatively small number of voters participated due to a boycott by the parties and a request to abstain from the influential UGTT union, which is heavily represented in public companies. While President Saed still enjoys some support from the working classes, the implementation of reforms will be hampered by a weaker economy, union opposition, and mistrust of liberal elites.'),(115,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' TRY ','Turkish Lira','Turkiye','After the elections in May 2023, Turkey\'s credit-driven economic boom will slow down because this model pushed for lower interest rates despite increasing inflation (85% y-o-y in October 2022). By the end of 2023, the central bank is anticipated to increase its policy rate from 8.5% in May 2023 to between 25 and 30%. Despite this, rate increases are still expected to be slow and unclear given the high level of anticipated inflation at the end of 2023 (between 60 and 65 percent) and the precarious state of the economy. Early in July 2023, the average interest rate for consumer loans was 48 percent, for commercial loans it was 25 percent, and for one-month deposits it was 28 percent. All of these rates were significantly higher than the bank\'s policy rate. Inflationary pressures on the economy will be exacerbated by the government\'s decision to raise taxes on a wide range of goods and services, the lira\'s sharp 30% depreciation between January and July 2023, an increase of 86% for the lowest-grade public employees after the elections, and a total increase of 107% in the minimum wage in 2023. As a result, within our projected horizon, a return to single-digit inflation will not be possible. Private demand will be hampered by persistently high inflation and tightening financial constraints. In the time following the March 2024 municipal elections, private consumption, which has been high for a while as a result of demand being pushed ahead by rising inflation, will have a reduced impact on growth. On the other hand, government spending will continue to have a beneficial impact due to the necessity for reconstruction following the earthquakes in February 2023 (estimated at roughly USD 26 billion) and other potential spending before the local elections. Banks will be reluctant to lend to the private sector due to tougher economic conditions for their customers, the requirement to match credit with Treasury purchases, and the maintenance of interest rate ceilings on commercial loans, all of which were imposed by the central bank as part of its macro-prudential measures. This will have an impact on investment growth and pose a serious risk to businesses since it makes it more difficult to manage cash flow, especially for those who are heavily indebted. If macroprudential restrictions on loans are relaxed, businesses may have more access to credit, but at a higher cost.'),(116,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' UGX ','Ugandan Shilling','Uganda','Uganda\'s economy slowed down in 2022 as a result of significant inflationary pressure. This prompted the central bank to raise its benchmark interest rate from 6.5% to 9% between May and August 2022. By putting pressure on credit, this increase has an impact on domestic private investment. The development of the oil fields Tilenga and Kingfisher, which are both close to Lake Albert, by the Chinese China NATIONAL offshore Oil Corporation and the French TotalEnergies will continue in 2023 in preparation for the start of production in 2025. The Mines and Minerals Act revision is anticipated to have positive effects on the economy as well. The elimination of the 5% tax imposed on exports of refined gold, which makes up the majority of the metal shipped, in July 2021 will theoretically be replaced by a levy of $100 per kilogram, which should increase the metal\'s hitherto nonexistent exports. Agriculture, which accounts for 23% of the GDP, will also be a key driver of growth because of the high demand and high prices for commodities like maize and coffee on the international and regional markets. With 6.65 million bags produced in the 2022–2023 season, Uganda is No. 2 in Africa and among the top ten coffee producers in the world. To lessen the impact of climate change on agricultural production, government authorities want to begin increasing forest cover from 2.6% to 15%. Income from agriculture will mitigate the effects of inflation on household consumption. Furthermore, tourism (which accounts for 10% of exports), particularly from the hotel sector, will contribute to increasing activity, barring unfavorable developments in the health situation (such as the Covid-19 and Ebola). Growth in manufacturing output should also occur (16% of GDP with agri-food, clothing, and construction materials), as well as the development of information and communication technologies (10% of exports), such as fintech, with the rise in mobile money transactions following Covid.\n'),(117,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' UAH ','Ukrainian Hryvnia','Ukraine','Increases in household spending and investments helped to assist the economic recovery in 2021, but the pre-pandemic level was not attained since a favorable base effect contributed to much of the increase. Additionally, Ukraine profited from a significant increase in the price of its main exports, particularly iron and wheat. Strong harvests should continue to support higher export quantities over the first several months of 2022. Due to increased base effects and the price stabilization of the most inflating components, inflation will slow down, but household consumption, which accounts for 74% of GDP, will continue to be the main engine of growth. The National Bank of Ukraine raised interest rates many times (to 8.5% as of November 2021) in response to the acceleration of inflation brought on by rising food and energy costs, which caused it to reach 11% in September 2021.\n \nThe rehabilitation process is still under risk from the COVID-19 pandemic. In autumn 2021, there have been more cases and hospitalizations despite the delayed immunization program. Ukraine has some of the lowest vaccination rates in all of Europe, with only 17.2% of the populace having received all recommended vaccinations as of the end of October 2021. Companies are also aware that it can slow down the recovery process. The risk of a new shutdown was cited as the top concern by 61% of questioned enterprises in the American Chamber of Commerce and Citi Ukraine poll, which was released in September 2021. On the other hand, 93% of the polled businesses argued that the government should take urgent action to enhance the business environment and draw in foreign investment by fighting corruption and enacting substantive judicial changes. The inadequate procedure for enacting changes does, in fact, have an influence on the country\'s investment climate and, as a result, the economy.'),(118,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' AED ','United Arab Emirates Dirham','United Arab Emirates','The United Arab Emirates (UAE)\'s economy should be able to withstand the subsequent rise in global oil demand that results from strong Asian growth and the higher oil prices that follow in 2024. The OPEC+ extension of oil output limits to the end of 2024 will still be a hindrance, though. The activity in the non-oil sector will continue to be strong. The government will be forced to expedite economic reforms (such as new commercial law allowing foreigners to fully own companies, new labor law shifting weekends from Friday and Saturday to Saturday and Sunday in 2022) in response to increasing competition from neighboring Saudi Arabia, which will have a favorable effect on investments (about 20% of GDP). A decline in inflation as well as an influx of foreign labor drawn by the economic diversification in Abu Dhabi and Dubai (where Emiratis make up around 10% of the overall population) will support private consumption, which accounts for close to 40% of GDP. Additionally, the UAE, which has maintained its neutrality in the conflict between Russia and Ukraine, has welcomed an increasing number of wealthy Russian immigrants and tourists, as well as high-tech workers who were fleeing Western sanctions. They will further increase consumption and the local real estate market. Additionally, the UAE will continue to play an increasingly important role as a trading hub for Russian gold since the war\'s outbreak in 2022. According to Russian customs, the UAE bought almost 76 tons of Russian gold valued close to USD 3 billion between February 2022 and March 2023, up from 1.3 tonnes in 2021. Similar to how restrictions from Switzerland have caused oil trading to shift to the UAE, increasing storage capabilities in Fujairah. These positions are anticipated to be strengthened by the UAE\'s political neutrality and strategic proximity to markets in Asia and Africa. Additionally, the government\'s plan to boost foreign tourism by increasing the number of visitors will be helpful. The two greatest sources of arrivals over the forecast period will be the Asia-Pacific and Middle-East areas (estimated at between 5.1 million and 5.09 arrivals in 2023, respectively, according to the BMI). Tourism revenue is projected to increase by 7% year over year to USD 43.7 billion (9% of GDP) in 2024, adding to the weight of private spending. However, government spending (which accounts for about 12% of GDP) will be mostly focused on business incentives and reforms rather than stimulus plans that will increase consumer spending. According to the peg to the dollar, the central bank is anticipated to follow the US Federal Reserve\'s lead, easing inflationary pressures.'),(119,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' GBP ','British Pound Sterling','United Kingdom','The \"mini-budget\" that was unveiled just two months earlier was reversed with the release of a new Autumn Statement in November that mostly concentrated on tax increases and spending reductions. Even while it will be less than in 2022, the public deficit will still be higher than it was before the pandemic. The Statement featured a number of household energy and cost-of-living support measures (+GBP 25 billion, 1.1% of GDP) as well as some support measures for public spending (+GBP 7.8 billion, 0.4% of GDP), including increased funding for the NHS, social care, and education. The Energy Bills Discount Scheme was unveiled by the government two months later (+ GBP 5.5 billion, 0.2% of GDP). Increased taxes, primarily on corporations, such as windfall taxes on energy producers and extraction businesses as well as other business taxes (+ GBP 7.1 billion, 0.3% of GDP), will only partially offset these costs. As a result, national debt will keep growing. Political unrest, inflation, and the BoE\'s policies all contribute to financing costs staying high. Since inflation-indexed bonds, which make up around 25% of the debt, were over 60% of the debt interest payments in November 2022, rising inflation has further impacted the budget. The BoE declared its intention to begin selling some of its holdings of government bonds (Gilts) in August 2022. It was originally planned to cut its overall gilt holdings by GBP 80 billion from September 2022 to September 2023, but due to Queen Elizabeth II\'s dying and the financial upheaval that followed the \"mini-budget,\" this was postponed by two months. Each quarter, the BoE plans to sell GBP 3.25 billion worth of Gilts in the short, medium, and long maturity sectors (a total of GBP 9.75 billion), with the remaining GBP 1.75 billion being used to stop reinvesting maturing bonds.'),(120,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' USD ','United States Dollar','United States Of America','Growth slowed down in 2022 following a significant rebound, which was limited by inflation and high interest rates. Due to the continued influence of these variables, growth will decline further in 2023. Although it is anticipated that inflation will continue its lowering trend from the second half of last year, it is still likely to be higher than the Federal Reserve\'s target rate of 2%. The Fed will continue a cycle of monetary tightening unseen in more than 40 years in the first quarter of 2022 after lifting its policy rate by 425 basis points in that year. The target rate band set by the Fed may be increased by an additional 75 basis points to 5.00% - 5.25%. Through 2023, rates are anticipated to stay at current stifling levels. Household consumption, which accounts for 68% of GDP, will therefore decline. Spending should continue to be distributed more towards services and away from products, which had profited from the outbreak. Therefore, the manufacturing sector might suffer. The easing of inflation, rising credit card debt, and a lack of saving, however, might help maintain household expenditures and (slimly) prevent a recession. Despite this, the unemployment rate is anticipated to increase from its low 3.7% at the end of 2022, which might cause people to be more cautious. Additionally, the climate of high interest rates will restrict investment. At the end of 2022, there will still be a sustainably comfortable cash position, but business capital spending plans will be scaled back. Residential investment ought to decline more. In 2023, there will be less construction activity as a result of the real estate market\'s decline. Contrary to 2022, the administration\'s investment projects (infrastructure, energy transition, semiconductor production) will permit a (small) positive contribution from government spending. In addition, the contribution of net exports will be constrained by a high dollar and a weak global economy.'),(121,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' UYU ','Uruguayan Peso','Uruguay','GDP growth is expected to slow down in 2023 after reaching its pre-COVID-19 level in 2022. Activity is anticipated to be driven by household consumption, which accounts for 59% of GDP, as inflationary pressures lessen throughout the year and the job market stays largely stable, particularly during a slow but steady recovery in tourism. Before the COVID-19 shock, this sector, which is important to the economy, contributed 16.4% to GDP and 16.3% to employment in 2019. The slowdown in activity in Argentina and Brazil, which are neighbors, may, however, have some impact on the recovery in tourism. The new UPM mill should begin to pay off in terms of international sales, which will increase exports of goods related to pulp. Additionally, growth of traditional exports (which account for 16% of GDP and include beef, soybean, dairy, rice, and wood products) will slow down from its strong performances in 2021 and 2022 due to weakening growth momentum in its main trading partners (China, Brazil, and the European Union), as well as an assumption of some easing in the price of agricultural commodities in 2023. Furthermore, the La Nia poses a downside risk to the crop in 2022–2023 for the third straight year. Finally, due to rising global borrowing rates and the cancellation of major projects like the UPM pulp factory and the Ferro Central Railway (both anticipated for Q1 2023), the increase of gross fixed investment might slow down. The majority of investments are anticipated to go toward expanding the export-related businesses, developing renewable energy sources (which now power over 90% of the nation\'s electrical system, including hydroelectric), and enhancing the road network.'),(122,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' VND ','Vietnamese Đồng','Vietnam','A resurgence in domestic demand and robust manufacturing production helped Vietnam achieve one of the highest economic growth rates in the region in 2022. Even though a steady rate of economic growth is anticipated, growth will slow down in 2023 due to a weaker global economy. Some of Vietnam\'s major trading partners, like the United States (which will account for 28.7% of its total exports of goods in 2021) and the European Union (which will account for 11.9%), are anticipated to see their demand decline. The European Union is one of the regions that has been facing significant recession concerns ever since the conflict in Ukraine. Vietnam\'s export prospects are deteriorating as a result of the slowing of China\'s economy, which is partly attributable to the country\'s tough Covid-19 policy. China is Vietnam\'s second-largest export market for goods (16.7% of the total in 2021). Making up 23.4% of the GDP in 2021, the manufacturing sector is anticipated to suffer from this. Despite this, the nation should continue to gain from the diversification of the global supply chain, which was initially sparked by the US-China trade war and strengthened by supply interruptions brought on by the pandemic. By luring in foreign capital, this has especially helped the growth of the textile, apparel, and electronics industries. Therefore, Foreign Direct Investment (FDI) inflows increased significantly after increasing by about 90% year over year in the first eight months of 2022. Since the government started treating Covid-19 as an endemic disease, domestic demand has undoubtedly increased, contributing to Vietnam\'s economic growth. After the government closed its borders to foreign travelers in March 2022, tourism—which contributed nearly 10% of GDP in 2019—will further drive local consumption. Although China, which accounted for about 32% of inbound visits in 2019, was the primary source of international tourists, the industry will continue be burdened by lingering travel restrictions in that country. With the support of controllable inflation, household spending (68% of GDP in 2021) should continue to grow strongly. Vietnam was largely shielded from the global 2022 inflation spike thanks to the government\'s influence over retail prices. Despite this, the State Bank of Vietnam (SBV) began tightening its monetary policy in September 2022 by raising interest rates to counter significant pressure for the Vietnamese Dong to devalue against the strong US dollar.'),(123,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' YER ','Yemeni Rial','Yemen','Yemen has been significantly impacted by the COVID-19 epidemic, which has forced the country to enter one of the most terrible humanitarian crises in the world. Yemen has already been seriously weakened by the civil war, which has been running for the past 7 years and has resulted in the deaths of 370,000 people (according to the UN). Because the nation is split into two areas, each with its own government, it is impossible to run the entire country in a coordinated manner. Mohammed al-Houti and his Revolutionary Council-led Houthi rebels have been in charge of the north and the country\'s capital Sana\'a since 2015. It is the loyalists in the south, with Aden, who have united the internationally recognized government of President Hadi and the Southern Transitional Council (autonomist), led by Aidarous al-Zubaid and backed by Saudi Arabia, since 2020. The battle has mostly continued unabated despite numerous attempts by the UN and the U.S., as well as a UN resolution calling on the Houthis to quit and placing an arms embargo and targeted penalties on them. Following a brief ceasefire after the COVID-19 epidemic, fighting returned to the south and even got worse in 2021. Almost 90% of the nation\'s food supply come from imports and humanitarian aid, and in November, pro-government forces withdrew from the important port of Hodeida, opening the door for the Houthis. In order to defend the Marib region from the Houthis\' entrance, it was decided to refocus on it. Up until that point, it had been seen as one of the remaining pockets of stability in the nation. The vast oil reserves in this final area of the north that is under government control are envious. In spite of this, the Houthis were able to encircle the same-named city, forcing tens of thousands of inhabitants to flee. The Saudi-led military coalition of Gulf states bombed targets in reaction to drone attacks on Saudi sites.'),(124,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,' ZWL ','Zimbabwean Dollar','Zimbabwe','After two straight years of contraction brought on by shocks related to Cyclone Idai, drought, and the Covid-19 epidemic, activity recovered in 2021 and 2022. Higher agricultural yields and mining activity—80% of which were exported, including 47% of gold and nickel—supported the recovery. In 2023, a moderate continuation of the trend is anticipated, with household spending and mining exports continuing to be the primary drivers. An expansionary fiscal policy in the run-up to the elections and a brief dip in inflation should allow consumption to pick up in the first half of the year. However, the impact on growth should be lessened by the increase in imports associated with the weakened manufacturing base. Due to a 10% increase in the amount of arable land being cultivated, which was already abundant the previous season, the autumn 2022 harvest saw a significant increase in the production of wheat. The two-thirds of the people that depend on agriculture ought to gain from this. Stocks of maize, a major crop, were equivalent to 12 months\' worth of usage in December 2022. However, due to high international prices and farmers\' reluctance to produce their harvest in unfavorable conditions, food insecurity is not anticipated to decrease (26.6% of the population was affected in January 2023, according to the WFP).');
